S100_FC_FeatureCatalogue.name: S-101
S100_FC_FeatureCatalogue.scope: Ocean, Coastal, Ports and Harbors. Excludes Inland waters.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Based On Fixed Marks
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: A straight route (known as a recommended track, range or leading line), which comprises: a. at least two structures (usually beacons or daymarks) and/or natural features, which may carry lights and/or top-marks. The structures/features are positioned so that when observed to be in line, a vessel can follow a known bearing with safety. (Adapted from International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA Aids to Navigation Guide, 1990); or b. a single structure or natural feature, which may carry lights and/or a topmark, and a specified bearing which can be followed with safety. (S-57 Edition 3.1, Appendix A Chapter 2, Page 2.72, November 2000, as amended).

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Beacon Shape
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Describes the characteristic geometric form of the beacon.

listedValue.label: Stake, Pole, Perch, Post
listedValue.definition: An elongated wood or metal pole, driven into the ground or seabed, which serves as a navigational aid or a support for a navigational aid.

listedValue.label: Withy
listedValue.definition: A tree without roots stuck or spoiled into the bottom of the sea to serve as a navigational aid.

listedValue.label: Beacon Tower
listedValue.definition: A solid structure of the order of 10 metres in height used as a navigational aid.

listedValue.label: Pile Beacon
listedValue.definition: A long heavy timber(s) or section(s) of steel, wood, concrete, etc., forced into the seabed to serve as an aid to navigation or as a support for an aid to navigation.

listedValue.label: Cairn
listedValue.definition: A mound of stones, usually conical or pyramidal, raised as a landmark or to designate a point of importance in surveying.

listedValue.label: Buoyant Beacon
listedValue.definition: A tall spar-like beacon fitted with a permanently submerged buoyancy chamber, the lower end of the body is secured to seabed sinker either by a flexible joint or by a cable under tension.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Building Shape
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The specific shape of the building.

listedValue.label: High-Rise Building
listedValue.definition: A building having many storeys.

listedValue.label: Pyramid
listedValue.definition: A polyhedron of which one face is a polygon of any number of sides, and the other faces are triangles with a common vertex.

listedValue.label: Cylindrical
listedValue.definition: Shaped like a cylinder, which is a solid geometrical figure generated by straight lines fixed in direction and describing with one of its points a closed curve, especially a circle.

listedValue.label: Spherical
listedValue.definition: Shaped like a sphere, which is a body the surface of which is at all points equidistant from the centre.

listedValue.label: Cubic
listedValue.definition: A shape the sides of which are six equal squares; a regular hexahedron.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Buoy Shape
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The principal shape and/or design of a buoy.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: The principal shapes are those recommended in the International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA System.

listedValue.label: Conical
listedValue.definition: The upper part of the body above the water-line, or the greater part of the superstructure, has approximately the shape or the appearance of a pointed cone with the point upwards.

listedValue.label: Can
listedValue.definition: The upper part of the body above the water-line, or the greater part of the superstructure, has the shape of a cylinder, or a truncated cone that approximates to a cylinder, with a flat end uppermost.

listedValue.label: Spherical
listedValue.definition: Shaped like a sphere, which is a body the surface of which is at all points equidistant from the centre.

listedValue.label: Pillar
listedValue.definition: The upper part of the body above the water-line, or the greater part of the superstructure is a narrow vertical structure, pillar or lattice tower.

listedValue.label: Spar
listedValue.definition: The upper part of the body above the water-line, or the greater part of the superstructure, has the form of a pole, or of a very long cylinder, floating upright.

listedValue.label: Barrel
listedValue.definition: The upper part of the body above the water-line, or the greater part of the superstructure, has the form of a barrel or cylinder floating horizontally.

listedValue.label: Superbuoy
listedValue.definition: A very large buoy designed to carry a signal light of high luminous intensity at a high elevation.

listedValue.label: Ice Buoy
listedValue.definition: A specially constructed shuttle shaped buoy which is used in ice conditions.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Buried Depth
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The depth below the sea bed to which an object is buried.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Call Sign
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The designated call-sign of a radio station, pilot, ....

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Airport/Airfield
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of airport/airfield based on the primary aircraft and user group.

listedValue.label: Military Aeroplane Airport
listedValue.definition: A large military airfield usually equipped with a control tower, hangars and accommodation for the receiving and discharging of passengers or cargo.

listedValue.label: Civil Aeroplane Airport
listedValue.definition: A large airfield usually equipped with a control tower, hangars and accommodation for the receiving and discharging of passengers or cargo.

listedValue.label: Military Heliport
listedValue.definition: A landing place for helicopters controlled by the military.

listedValue.label: Civil Heliport
listedValue.definition: A landing place for helicopters, often the roof of a building.

listedValue.label: Glider Airfield
listedValue.definition: An area of land set aside for the take-off and landing of gliders.

listedValue.label: Small Planes Airfield
listedValue.definition: An area of land set aside for the take-off and landing of small aeroplanes.

listedValue.label: Emergency Airfield
listedValue.definition: An area of land set aside for the take-off and landing of aeroplanes or helicopters in times of emergency.

listedValue.label: Search and Rescue Airfield
listedValue.definition: An area of land set aside for the take-off and landing of aeroplanes or helicopters in times of search and rescue.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Anchorage
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of an area where different use types of vessel can remain static.

listedValue.label: Unrestricted Anchorage
listedValue.definition: An area in which vessels anchor or may anchor.

listedValue.label: Deep Water Anchorage
listedValue.definition: An area in which vessels of deep draught anchor or may anchor.

listedValue.label: Tanker Anchorage
listedValue.definition: An area in which tankers anchor or may anchor.

listedValue.label: Explosives Anchorage
listedValue.definition: An area set apart for anchored ships discharging or receiving explosives.

listedValue.label: Quarantine Anchorage
listedValue.definition: An area where a vessel anchors when satisfying quarantine regulations.

listedValue.label: Seaplane Anchorage
listedValue.definition: An area in which sea-planes anchor or may anchor.

listedValue.label: Small Craft Anchorage
listedValue.definition: An area in which yachts and small boats anchor or may anchor.

listedValue.label: Small Craft Mooring Area
listedValue.definition: An area in which yachts and small boats moor.

listedValue.label: Anchorage for Periods Up To 24 Hours
listedValue.definition: An area in which vessels anchor or may anchor for periods of up to 24 hours.

listedValue.label: Anchorage for a Limited Period of Time
listedValue.definition: An area in which vessels may anchor for a period of time not to exceed a specific limit.

listedValue.label: Waiting Anchorage
listedValue.definition: An area in which vessels anchor or may anchor while waiting, for example, for access to a port or berth.

listedValue.label: Reported Anchorage
listedValue.definition: A location not defined by a regulatory authority that has been reported to be suitable and safe for anchoring.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Bridge
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of structures spanning and providing passage over a gap or barrier, such as a river or roadway.

listedValue.label: Fixed Bridge
listedValue.definition: A bridge having permanent horizontal and vertical alignment.

listedValue.label: Opening Bridge
listedValue.definition: A bridge that is closed when set for carrying road traffic and open when set to permit marine traffic to pass through the waterway it crosses. Modern opening (movable) bridges are either bascule, vertical lift or swing.

listedValue.label: Swing Bridge
listedValue.definition: A movable bridge (or span thereof) which rotates in a horizontal plane about a vertical pivot to allow the passage of vessels.

listedValue.label: Lifting Bridge
listedValue.definition: A movable bridge (or span thereof) which is capable of being lifted vertically to allow vessels to pass beneath.

listedValue.label: Bascule Bridge
listedValue.definition: A counterpoise bridge rotated in a vertical plane about an axis at one or both ends.

listedValue.label: Pontoon Bridge
listedValue.definition: A fixed floating bridge supported by pontoons.

listedValue.label: Drawbridge
listedValue.definition: A general name for bridges of which part or the entire span of the bridge may be raised or drawn aside to allow ships to pass through.

listedValue.label: Transporter Bridge
listedValue.definition: Consists of towers on each side of the watercourse connected by a system of girders on which a carriage runs.

listedValue.label: Footbridge
listedValue.definition: A bridge structure used only for pedestrian traffic.

listedValue.label: Viaduct
listedValue.definition: A structure consisting of a series of arches or towers supporting a roadway, waterway, etc., across a depression, etc.

listedValue.label: Aqueduct
listedValue.definition: A bridge supporting an artificially elevated channel, for the conveyance of water.

listedValue.label: Suspension Bridge
listedValue.definition: A fixed bridge consisting of either a roadway or a truss suspended from two or more cables which pass over towers and are anchored by backstays to a firm foundation.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Built-Up Area
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Human settlement classification.

listedValue.label: Urban Area
listedValue.definition: An area predominantly occupied by man-made structures used for residential, commercial, and industrial purposes.

listedValue.label: Settlement
listedValue.definition: A continuously occupied concentration of tents or lightweight fixed structures (for example: huts) serving as residences.

listedValue.label: Village
listedValue.definition: A self-contained group of houses and associated buildings, usually in a country area.

listedValue.label: Town
listedValue.definition: An inhabited place larger and more regularly built and with more complete and independent local government than a village but not incorporated as a city.

listedValue.label: City
listedValue.definition: A major town inhabited by a large permanent community with all essential services.

listedValue.label: Holiday Village
listedValue.definition: A complex for holiday-makers with cottages, shops, and entertainment, on site, which is mainly populated on a seasonal basis.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Cable
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of the cable based on the services provided.

listedValue.label: Power Line
listedValue.definition: A cable that transmits or distributes electrical power.

listedValue.label: Transmission Line
listedValue.definition: Multiple un-insulated cables usually supported by steel lattice towers. Such features are generally more prominent than normal power lines.

listedValue.label: Telephone
listedValue.definition: A cable that transmits telephone signals.

listedValue.label: Telegraph
listedValue.definition: An apparatus, system or process for communication at a distance by electric transmission over wire.

listedValue.label: Mooring Cable
listedValue.definition: A chain or very strong fibre or wire rope used to anchor or moor vessels or buoys.

listedValue.label: Ferry
listedValue.definition: A vessel for transporting passengers, vehicles, and/or goods across a stretch of water, especially as a regular service.

listedValue.label: Fibre Optic Cable
listedValue.definition: A cable made of glass or plastic fiber designed to guide light along its length, fibre optic cables are widely used in fiber-optic communication, which permits transmission over longer distances and at higher data rates than other forms of communication.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Canal
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of an artificial waterway used for travel, drainage, or irrigation.

listedValue.label: Transportation
listedValue.definition: A canal used for navigation as part of a transport system.

listedValue.label: Drainage
listedValue.definition: A canal used to drain excess water from surrounding land.

listedValue.label: Irrigation
listedValue.definition: A canal used to supply water for the purpose of irrigation.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Cardinal Mark
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The four quadrants (north, east, south and west) are bounded by the true bearings NW-NE, NE-SE, SE-SW and SW-NW taken from the point of interest. A cardinal mark is named after the quadrant in which it is placed. The name of the cardinal mark indicates that it should be passed to the named side of the mark.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: Cardinal marks are used in conjunction with the compass to indicate where a mariner will find safe navigable water.Cardinal marks do not have a distinctive shape but are normally pillar or spar. They are always painted in yellow and black horizontal bands and their distinctive double cone top-marks are always black. (Note that such top-marks are encoded as separate TOPMAR objects). Cardinal marks may also have a special system of flashing white lights and if such lights are fitted they are encoded as separate LIGHTS objects.

listedValue.label: North Cardinal Mark
listedValue.definition: Quadrant bounded by the true bearing NW-NE taken from the point of interest; it should be passed to the north side of the mark.

listedValue.label: East Cardinal Mark
listedValue.definition: Quadrant bounded by the true bearing NE-SE taken from the point of interest. It should be passed to the east side of the mark.

listedValue.label: South Cardinal Mark
listedValue.definition: Quadrant bounded by the true bearing SE-SW taken from the point of interest; it should be passed to the south side of the mark.

listedValue.label: West Cardinal Mark
listedValue.definition: Quadrant bounded by the true bearing SW-NW taken from the point of interest; it should be passed to the west side of the mark.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Checkpoint
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of a place where vehicles or travellers are stopped for identification or inspection.

listedValue.label: Custom
listedValue.definition: Serves as a government checkpoint where customs duties are collected, the flow of goods are regulated and restrictions enforced, and shipments or vehicles are cleared for entering or leaving a country.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Coastline
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Physical condition of the coastline.

listedValue.label: Steep Coast
listedValue.definition: A coast backed by rock or earth cliffs, gives a good radar return and is useful for visual identification from a considerable distance off, where cliffs alternate with low lying coast along the shoreline.

listedValue.label: Flat Coast
listedValue.definition: A level coast with no obvious topographic features.

listedValue.label: Glacier, Seaward End
listedValue.definition: Projecting seaward extension of glacier, usually afloat.

listedValue.label: Mangrove
listedValue.definition: One of several genera of tropical trees or shrubs which produce many prop roots and grow along low lying coasts into shallow water.

listedValue.label: Marshy Shore
listedValue.definition: A shoreline area made up of spongy land saturated with water. It may have a shallow covering of water, usually with a considerable amount of vegetation appearing above the surface.

listedValue.label: Ice Coast
listedValue.definition: A vertical cliff forming the seaward edge of an ice shelf, ranging in height from 2m to 50m or more above sea level.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Conveyor
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of conveyor used for moving goods from one location to another.

listedValue.label: Aerial Cableway
listedValue.definition: A transportation system consisting of load cables strung between pylons on which carrier units (for example: cars or buckets intended to transport people, material, and/or equipment) are suspended.

listedValue.label: Belt Conveyor
listedValue.definition: A conveyor along which material or people are transported by means of a moving belt.

listedValue.label: Flume
listedValue.definition: An artificial channel, usually an inclined chute or trough, for carrying water to furnish power, transport logs down a mountainside, etc.

listedValue.label: Lift/Elevator
listedValue.definition: Any of various mechanical devices for raising objects or materials.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Crane
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of machines used for hoisting and moving heavy objects.

listedValue.label: Container Crane/Gantry
listedValue.definition: A high speed, shore-based crane used in the lift-on/lift-off operation of specially constructed containers.

listedValue.label: Sheerlegs
listedValue.definition: A tripodal structure used in dockyards and harbours for stepping masts or lifting loads in to and out of vessels.

listedValue.label: Travelling Crane
listedValue.definition: A crane mounted on rails (track) that can move (usually parallel to the wharf face) in order to load and unload cargo vessels.

listedValue.label: A-Frame
listedValue.definition: A type of crane shaped like the letter 'A'.

listedValue.label: Goliath Crane
listedValue.definition: A powerful travelling crane mounted on a movable gantry of large span.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Dam
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of a structure acting as barrier to water flow.

listedValue.label: Weir
listedValue.definition: A dam erected across a river to raise the level of the water. A fence of stakes set in a river or along the shore as a trap for fish. The word is now restricted to smaller works, the larger are called dams.

listedValue.label: Dam
listedValue.definition: A barrier to check or confine anything in motion; particularly one constructed to hold back water and raise its level to form a reservoir, or to prevent flooding.

listedValue.label: Flood Barrage
listedValue.definition: An opening dam across a channel which, when required, is closed to control flood waters.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Distance Mark
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of fixed and virtual distance marks.

listedValue.label: Distance Mark Not Physically Installed
listedValue.definition: A point at which a distance from an origin along a feature is given for information, but at which no specific marker exists.

listedValue.label: Visible Mark, Pole
listedValue.definition: A point at which a distance from an origin along a feature is given for information and which is marked by a pole.

listedValue.label: Visible Mark, Board
listedValue.definition: A point at which a distance from an origin along a feature is given for information and which is marked by a board.

listedValue.label: Visible Mark, Unknown Shape
listedValue.definition: A point at which a distance from an origin along a feature is given for information and which is physically marked, but the shape of the mark is not known or not given.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Dock
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of vessel dock.

listedValue.label: Tidal
listedValue.definition: A dock which is open to the sea and in which the water level is affected by tides.

listedValue.label: Wet Dock
listedValue.definition: A dock in which water can be maintained at any level by closing a gate when the water is at the desired level.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Dumping Ground
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of an area based on the type of waste being disposed of.

listedValue.label: Chemical Waste Dumping Ground
listedValue.definition: An area at sea where chemical waste is dumped.

listedValue.label: Nuclear Waste Dumping Ground
listedValue.definition: An area at sea where nuclear waste is dumped.

listedValue.label: Explosives Dumping Ground
listedValue.definition: An area at sea where explosives are dumped.

listedValue.label: Spoil Ground
listedValue.definition: A sea area where dredged material is deposited.

listedValue.label: Vessel Dumping Ground
listedValue.definition: An area at sea where disused vessels are scuttled.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Fence
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of a physical boundary.

listedValue.label: Fence
listedValue.definition: A man-made barrier of relatively light structure used as an enclosure or boundary.

listedValue.label: Hedge
listedValue.definition: A continuous growth of shrubbery planted as a fence, a boundary or a wind break.

listedValue.label: Wall
listedValue.definition: A solid man-made barrier of generally heavy material used as an enclosure, boundary, or for protection.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Ferry
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of the manoeuvrability of the ferry vessel, not the various types of ferry vessel.

listedValue.label: Free Moving Ferry
listedValue.definition: A ferry which may have routes that vary with weather, tide and traffic.

listedValue.label: Cable Ferry
listedValue.definition: A ferry that follows a fixed route guided by a cable.

listedValue.label: Ice Ferry
listedValue.definition: A winter-time ferry which crosses a lead.

listedValue.label: High Speed Ferry
listedValue.definition: A high speed water vessel for civilian use.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Fishing Facility
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of fishing facility provided based on different fishing methods.

listedValue.label: Fishing Stake
listedValue.definition: Poles or stakes placed in shallow water to outline a fishing ground or to catch fish.

listedValue.label: Fish Trap
listedValue.definition: A structure (usually portable) for catching fish.

listedValue.label: Fish Weir
listedValue.definition: A fence of stakes or stones set in a river or along the shore to trap fish.

listedValue.label: Tunny Net
listedValue.definition: A net built at sea for catching tunny.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Fog Signal
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of the various means of generating the fog signal.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: The classification 'horn' is the generic term for fog signals 'nautophone', 'reed' and 'tyfon'.

listedValue.label: Explosive
listedValue.definition: A signal produced by the firing of explosive charges.

listedValue.label: Diaphone
listedValue.definition: A diaphone uses compressed air and generally emits a powerful low-pitched sound, which often concludes with a brief sound of suddenly lowered pitch, termed the 'grunt'.

listedValue.label: Siren
listedValue.definition: A type of fog signal apparatus which produces sound by virtue of the passage of air through slots or holes in a revolving disk.

listedValue.label: Nautophone
listedValue.definition: A horn having a diaphragm oscillated by electricity.

listedValue.label: Reed
listedValue.definition: [1] A reed uses compressed air and emits a weak, high pitched sound. [2] Any of various water or marsh plants with a firm stem. (Concise Oxford English Dictionary)

listedValue.label: Tyfon
listedValue.definition: A diaphragm horn which operates under the influence of compressed air or steam.

listedValue.label: Bell
listedValue.definition: A ringing sound with a short range.

listedValue.label: Whistle
listedValue.definition: A distinctive sound made by a jet of air passing through an orifice. The apparatus may be operated automatically, by hand or by air being forced up a tube by waves acting on a buoy.

listedValue.label: Gong
listedValue.definition: A sound produced by vibration of a disc when struck.

listedValue.label: Horn
listedValue.definition: A horn uses compressed air or electricity to vibrate a diaphragm and exists in a variety of types which differ greatly in their sound and power.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Fortified Structure
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of the different types of fortified structure.

listedValue.label: Castle
listedValue.definition: A large fortified building or structure.

listedValue.label: Fort
listedValue.definition: A fortified enclosure, building, or position able to be defended against an enemy.

listedValue.label: Battery
listedValue.definition: A fortified structure on which artillery is mounted.

listedValue.label: Blockhouse
listedValue.definition: A concrete structure strengthened to give protection against enemy fire, with apertures to allow defensive gunfire.

listedValue.label: Fortified Tower
listedValue.definition: A small circular fort with very thick walls (for example Martello tower).

listedValue.label: Redoubt
listedValue.definition: An outwork or fieldwork usually square or polygonal and without flanking defences.

listedValue.label: Fortified Submarine Shelter
listedValue.definition: A fortified pen to hold submarines.

listedValue.label: Rampart
listedValue.definition: Anything serving as a bulwark or defence.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Gate
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of a structure that can be swung, drawn, or lowered to block an entrance or a passageway.

listedValue.label: Flood Barrage Gate
listedValue.definition: An opening gate used to control flood water.

listedValue.label: Caisson
listedValue.definition: A steel structure used for closing the entrance of locks, wet and dry docks.

listedValue.label: Lock Gate
listedValue.definition: Pair of massive hinged doors at each end of a lock.

listedValue.label: Dyke Gate
listedValue.definition: An opening gate in a dyke.

listedValue.label: Sluice
listedValue.definition: A sliding gate or other contrivance for changing the level of a body of water by controlling the flow into or out of it.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Harbour Facility
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of harbour use.

listedValue.label: RoRo Terminal
listedValue.definition: A terminal for roll-on roll-off ferries.

listedValue.label: Ferry Terminal
listedValue.definition: A terminal for passenger and vehicle ferries.

listedValue.label: Fishing Harbour
listedValue.definition: A harbour with facilities for fishing boats.

listedValue.label: Yacht Harbour/Marina
listedValue.definition: A harbour facility for small boats, yachts, etc., where supplies, repairs, and various services are available.

listedValue.label: Naval Base
listedValue.definition: A centre of operations for naval vessels.

listedValue.label: Tanker Terminal
listedValue.definition: A terminal for the bulk handling of liquid cargoes.

listedValue.label: Passenger Terminal
listedValue.definition: A terminal for the loading and unloading of passengers.

listedValue.label: Shipyard
listedValue.definition: A place where ships are built or repaired.

listedValue.label: Container Terminal
listedValue.definition: A terminal with facilities to load/unload or store shipping containers.

listedValue.label: Bulk Terminal
listedValue.definition: A terminal for the handling of bulk materials such as iron ore, coal, etc.

listedValue.label: Ship Lift
listedValue.definition: A platform powered by synchronous electric motors (for example syncrolift) used to lift vessels (larger than boats) in and out of the water.

listedValue.label: Straddle Carrier
listedValue.definition: A wheeled vehicle designed to lift and carry containers or vessels within its own framework. It is used for moving, and sometimes stacking, shipping containers and vessels.

listedValue.label: Service Harbour
listedValue.definition: A harbour within which the floating equipment (dredges, tugs ...) of harbour services are stationed.

listedValue.label: Pilotage Service
listedValue.definition: The services of a person who directs the movements of a vessel through pilot waters, usually a person who has demonstrated extensive knowledge of channels, aids to navigation, dangers to navigation, etc., in a particular area and is licensed for that area, are available.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Hulk
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of an old or unseaworthy ship used for a new function.

listedValue.label: Floating Restaurant
listedValue.definition: A permanently moored floating structure (for example: an old ship) that is used as a restaurant.

listedValue.label: Historic Ship
listedValue.definition: A ship of historical interest permanently moored as a tourist attraction.

listedValue.label: Floating Museum
listedValue.definition: A permanently moored floating structure (for example: an old ship) that is used as a museum.

listedValue.label: Floating Accommodation
listedValue.definition: A permanently moored floating structure (for example: an old ship) that is used for accommodation.

listedValue.label: Floating Breakwater
listedValue.definition: A permanently moored floating structure, often constructed from old ships, used as a breakwater.

listedValue.label: Casino
listedValue.definition: A permanently moored floating structure, such as an old ship, used as a casino boat.

listedValue.label: Training Vessel
listedValue.definition: A permanently moored floating structure, often constructed from old ships, used for training purposes.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Ice
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of ice.

listedValue.label: Fast Ice
listedValue.definition: Sea ice which remains fast, generally in the position where originally formed, and which may attain a considerable thickness. It is found along coasts, where it is attached to the shore, or over shoals, where it may be held in position by islands, grounded icebergs or grounded polar ice.

listedValue.label: Glacier
listedValue.definition: A mass of snow and ice continuously moving from higher to lower ground or, if afloat, continuously spreading.

listedValue.label: Polar Ice
listedValue.definition: Sea ice that is more than one year old (in contrast to winter ice). The WMO code defines polar ice as any sea ice more than one year old and more than 3 metres thick.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Installation Buoy
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of fixed installation buoy.

listedValue.label: Catenary Anchor Leg Mooring
listedValue.definition: Incorporates a large buoy which remains on the surface at all times and is moored by 4 or more anchors. Mooring hawsers and cargo hoses lead from a turntable on top of the buoy, so that the buoy does not turn as the ship swings to wind and stream.

listedValue.label: Single Buoy Mooring
listedValue.definition: A large mooring buoy used by tankers to load and unload in port approaches or in offshore oil and gas fields.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Landmark
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of prominent cultural and natural features in the landscape.

listedValue.label: Cairn
listedValue.definition: A mound of stones, usually conical or pyramidal, raised as a landmark or to designate a point of importance in surveying.

listedValue.label: Cemetery
listedValue.definition: A site and associated structures devoted to the burial of the dead.

listedValue.label: Chimney
listedValue.definition: A vertical structure containing a passage or flue for discharging smoke and gases of combustion.

listedValue.label: Dish Aerial
listedValue.definition: A parabolic aerial for the receipt and transmission of high frequency radio signals.

listedValue.label: Flagstaff
listedValue.definition: A staff or pole on which flags are raised.

listedValue.label: Flare Stack
listedValue.definition: A tall structure used for burning-off waste oil or gas.

listedValue.label: Mast
listedValue.definition: A relatively tall structure usually held vertical by guy lines.

listedValue.label: Windsock
listedValue.definition: A tapered fabric sleeve mounted so as to catch and swing with the wind, thus indicating the wind direction.

listedValue.label: Monument
listedValue.definition: A structure erected and/or maintained as a memorial to a person and/or event.

listedValue.label: Column/Pillar
listedValue.definition: A cylindrical or slightly tapering body of considerably greater length than diameter erected vertically.

listedValue.label: Memorial Plaque
listedValue.definition: A slab of metal, usually ornamented, erected as a memorial to a person or event.

listedValue.label: Obelisk
listedValue.definition: A tapering shaft usually of stone or concrete, square or rectangular in section, with a pyramidal apex.

listedValue.label: Statue
listedValue.definition: A representation of a living being, sculptured, moulded, or cast in a variety of materials (for example: marble, metal, or plaster).

listedValue.label: Cross
listedValue.definition: A monument, or other structure in form of a cross.

listedValue.label: Dome
listedValue.definition: A landmark comprising a hemispherical or spheroidal shaped structure.

listedValue.label: Radar Scanner
listedValue.definition: A device used for directing a radar beam through a search pattern.

listedValue.label: Tower
listedValue.definition: A relatively tall, narrow structure that may either stand alone or may form part of another structure.

listedValue.label: Windmill
listedValue.definition: A system of vanes attached to a tower and driven by wind (excluding wind turbines).

listedValue.label: Spire/Minaret
listedValue.definition: A tall conical or pyramid-shaped structure often built on the roof or tower of a building, especially a church or mosque.

listedValue.label: Large Rock or Boulder on Land
listedValue.definition: An isolated rocky formation or a single large stone.

listedValue.label: Triangulation Mark
listedValue.definition: A recoverable point on the earth, whose geographic position has been determined by angular methods with geodetic instruments. A triangulation point is a selected point, which has been marked with a station mark, or it is a conspicuous natural or artificial feature.

listedValue.label: Boundary Mark
listedValue.definition: A marker identifying the location of a surveyed boundary line.

listedValue.label: Observation Wheel
listedValue.definition: Wheels with passenger cars mounted external to the rim and independently rotated by electric motors.

listedValue.label: Torii
listedValue.definition: A form of decorative gateway or portal, consisting of two upright wooden posts connected at the top by two horizontal crosspieces, commonly found at the entrance to Shinto temples.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Land Region
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: General terms for describing landscapes.

listedValue.label: Fen
listedValue.definition: A type of bog, especially a low-lying area, wholly or partly covered with water and dominated by grass-like plants, grasses, sedges and reeds.

listedValue.label: Marsh
listedValue.definition: An area of wet, often spongy ground that is subject to frequent flooding or tidal inundations, but not considered to be continually under water. It is characterized by the growth of non woody plants and by the lack of trees.

listedValue.label: Bog
listedValue.definition: Wet spongy ground consisting of decaying vegetation, which retains stagnant water, too soft to bear the weight of any heavy body.

listedValue.label: Heathland
listedValue.definition: A tract of wasteland peat bog, usually covered by a low scrubby growth, but may have scattered small open water holes.

listedValue.label: Mountain Range
listedValue.definition: A series of connected and aligned mountains or mountain ridges.

listedValue.label: Lowlands
listedValue.definition: Low and relatively level land at a lower elevation than adjoining areas.

listedValue.label: Canyon Lands
listedValue.definition: A relatively narrow, deep depression with steep sides, the bottom of which generally has a continuous slope.

listedValue.label: Paddy Field
listedValue.definition: A piece of land set aside for crops which are periodically flooded (for example rice paddy).

listedValue.label: Agricultural Land
listedValue.definition: Of or pertaining to the science or practice of cultivating the soil and rearing animals.

listedValue.label: Savanna/Grassland
listedValue.definition: An open grassy plain with few or no trees in a tropical or subtropical region; a tract covered mainly by grasses that have little or no woody tissue.

listedValue.label: Parkland
listedValue.definition: A piece of ground kept for ornament and/or recreation or maintained in its natural state as a public property or area.

listedValue.label: Swamp
listedValue.definition: An area of spongy land saturated with water. It may have a shallow covering of water, usually with a considerable amount of vegetation appearing above the surface.

listedValue.label: Landslide
listedValue.definition: The sliding down of a mass of land on a mountain or cliff-side; land which has so fallen.

listedValue.label: Lava Flow
listedValue.definition: The substance that results from the cooling of molten rock.

listedValue.label: Salt Pan
listedValue.definition: Shallow pools of brackish water used for the natural evaporation of sea water to obtain salt.

listedValue.label: Moraine
listedValue.definition: Any accumulation of loose material deposited by a glacier.

listedValue.label: Crater
listedValue.definition: Bowl-shaped cavity, at the summit or on the side of a volcano.

listedValue.label: Cave
listedValue.definition: A natural subterranean chamber or series of chambers open to the earth's surface.

listedValue.label: Rock Column or Pinnacle
listedValue.definition: Any high tower or spire-shaped pillar of rock, alone or cresting a summit.

listedValue.label: Cay
listedValue.definition: A small insular feature usually with scant vegetation usually of sand or coral. Often applied to smaller coral shoals.

listedValue.label: Wadi
listedValue.definition: A watercourse that is permanently dry or dry except for the rainy season.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Lateral Mark
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of lateral marks in the IALA Buoyage System.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: There are two international buoyage regions, A and B, between which lateral marks differ. When top-marks, retro reflectors and/or lights are fitted to these marks, they are encoded as separate features.

listedValue.label: Port-Hand Lateral Mark
listedValue.definition: Indicates the port boundary of a navigational channel or suggested route when proceeding in the "conventional direction of buoyage".

listedValue.label: Starboard-Hand Lateral Mark
listedValue.definition: Indicates the starboard boundary of a navigational channel or suggested route when proceeding in the "conventional direction of buoyage".

listedValue.label: Preferred Channel to Starboard Lateral Mark
listedValue.definition: At a point where a channel divides, when proceeding in the "conventional direction of buoyage", the preferred channel (or primary route) is indicated by a modified port-hand lateral mark.

listedValue.label: Preferred Channel to Port Lateral Mark
listedValue.definition: At a point where a channel divides, when proceeding in the "conventional direction of buoyage", the preferred channel (or primary route) is indicated by a modified starboard-hand lateral mark.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Light
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of different light types.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: All lights are considered to be marine lights unless the category of light indicates otherwise.

listedValue.label: Leading Light
listedValue.definition: A light associated with other lights so as to form a leading line to be followed.

listedValue.label: Aero Light
listedValue.definition: An aero light is established for aeronautical navigation and may be of higher power than marine lights and visible from well offshore.

listedValue.label: Flood Light
listedValue.definition: A broad beam light used to illuminate a structure or area.

listedValue.label: Strip Light
listedValue.definition: A light whose source has a linear form generally horizontal, which can reach a length of several metres.

listedValue.label: Subsidiary Light
listedValue.definition: A light placed on or near the support of a main light and having a special use in navigation.

listedValue.label: Spotlight
listedValue.definition: A powerful light focused so as to illuminate a small area.

listedValue.label: Front
listedValue.definition: Term used with leading lights to describe the position of the light on the lead as viewed from seaward.

listedValue.label: Rear
listedValue.definition: Term used with leading lights to describe the position of the light on the lead as viewed from seaward.

listedValue.label: Lower
listedValue.definition: Term used with leading lights to describe the position of the light on the lead as viewed from seaward.

listedValue.label: Upper
listedValue.definition: Term used with leading lights to describe the position of the light on the lead as viewed from seaward.

listedValue.label: Emergency
listedValue.definition: A light available as a backup to a main light which will be illuminated should the main light fail.

listedValue.label: Bearing Light
listedValue.definition: A light which enables its approximate bearing to be obtained without the use of a compass.

listedValue.label: Horizontally Disposed
listedValue.definition: A group of lights of identical character and almost identical position, that are disposed horizontally.

listedValue.label: Vertically Disposed
listedValue.definition: A group of lights of identical character and almost identical position, that are disposed vertically.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Marine Farm/Culture
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of an area of water devoted to the raising, breeding, or production of a specific aquatic animal.

listedValue.label: Crustaceans
listedValue.definition: Hard shelled animals, for example crabs or lobsters.

listedValue.label: Edible Bivalve Molluscs
listedValue.definition: A two-part hinged external shell covering that contains a soft-bodied invertebrate.

listedValue.label: Fish
listedValue.definition: Vertebrate cold blooded animal with gills, living in water.

listedValue.label: Seaweed
listedValue.definition: The general name for marine plants of the Algae class which grow in long narrow ribbons.

listedValue.label: Pearl Culture Farm
listedValue.definition: An area where pearls are artificially cultivated.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Military Practice Area
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of area by military use.

listedValue.label: Torpedo Exercise Area
listedValue.definition: An area within which exercises are carried out with torpedoes.

listedValue.label: Submarine Exercise Area
listedValue.definition: An area within which submarine exercises are carried out.

listedValue.label: Firing Danger Area
listedValue.definition: Areas for bombing and missile exercises.

listedValue.label: Mine-Laying Practice Area
listedValue.definition: An area within which mine laying exercises are carried out.

listedValue.label: Small Arms Firing Range
listedValue.definition: An area for shooting pistols, rifles and machine guns etc. at a target.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Mooring/Warping Facility
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: A place or structure to which a vessel can be secured.

listedValue.label: Dolphin
listedValue.definition: A post or group of posts, used for mooring or warping a vessel, or as an aid to navigation. The dolphin may be in the water, on a wharf or on the beach.

listedValue.label: Deviation Dolphin
listedValue.definition: A post or group of posts, which a vessel may swing around for compass adjustment.

listedValue.label: Bollard
listedValue.definition: Small shaped post, mounted on a wharf or dolphin used to secure ship's lines.

listedValue.label: Tie-Up Wall
listedValue.definition: A section of wall designated for tying-up vessels awaiting transit. Bollards and mooring devices are available for both large and small ships.

listedValue.label: Post or Pile
listedValue.definition: A long heavy timber or section of steel, wood, concrete, etc., forced into the seabed to serve as a mooring facility.

listedValue.label: Mooring Cable
listedValue.definition: A chain or very strong fibre or wire rope used to anchor or moor vessels or buoys.

listedValue.label: Mooring Buoy
listedValue.definition: A buoy secured to the bottom by permanent moorings with means for mooring a vessel by use of its anchor chain or mooring lines.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Navigation Line
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of route guidance given to vessels.

listedValue.label: Clearing Line
listedValue.definition: A straight line that marks the boundary between a safe and a dangerous area or that passes clear of a navigational danger.

listedValue.label: Transit Line
listedValue.definition: A line passing through one or more fixed marks.

listedValue.label: Leading Line Bearing a Recommended Track
listedValue.definition: A line passing through one or more clearly defined objects, along the path of which a vessel can approach safely up to a certain distance off.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Obstruction
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of objects that impede movement.

listedValue.label: Snag/Stump
listedValue.definition: A tree, branch or broken pile embedded in the ocean floor, river or lake bottom and not visible on the surface, forming thereby a hazard to vessels.

listedValue.label: Wellhead
listedValue.definition: A submarine structure projecting some distance above the seabed and capping a temporarily abandoned or suspended oil or gas well.

listedValue.label: Diffuser
listedValue.definition: A structure on an outfall through which liquids are discharged. The structure will usually project above the level of the outfall and can be an obstruction to navigation.

listedValue.label: Crib
listedValue.definition: A permanent marine structure usually designed to support or elevate pipelines; especially a structure enclosing a screening device at the offshore end of a potable water intake pipe. The structure is commonly a heavy timber enclosure that has been sunken with rocks or other debris.

listedValue.label: Fish Haven
listedValue.definition: Areas established by private interests, usually sport fishermen, to simulate natural reefs and wrecks that attract fish. The reefs are constructed by dumping assorted junk in areas which may be of very small extent or may stretch a considerable distance along a depth contour.

listedValue.label: Foul Area
listedValue.definition: An area of numerous unidentified dangers to navigation. The area serves as a warning to the mariner that all dangers are not identified individually and that navigation through the area may be hazardous.

listedValue.label: Ice Boom
listedValue.definition: Floating barriers, anchored to the bottom, used to deflect the path of floating ice in order to prevent the obstruction of locks, intakes, etc., and to prevent damage to bridge piers and other structures.

listedValue.label: Ground Tackle
listedValue.definition: Equipment such as anchors, concrete blocks, chains and cables, etc., used to position floating structures such as trot and mooring buoys etc.

listedValue.label: Boom
listedValue.definition: A floating barrier used to protect a river or harbour mouth or to create a sheltered area for storage purposes.

listedValue.label: Wave Energy Device
listedValue.definition: A device to extract energy from the surface motion of ocean waves or from pressure fluctuations below the surface.

listedValue.label: Subsurface Ocean Data Acquisition System
listedValue.definition: A submerged device, not being a ship, together with its appurtenant equipment, deployed at sea essentially for the purpose of collecting, storing or transmitting samples or data relating to the marine environment.

listedValue.label: Artificial Reef
listedValue.definition: A man-made structure that may mimic some of the characteristics of a natural reef, intended to attract sea life.

listedValue.label: Template
listedValue.definition: A structure placed on the sea floor below a drilling rig to guide the drill.

listedValue.label: Manifold
listedValue.definition: A large steel structure up to 20 metres in height above the sea floor, or a steel frame secured to the sea floor with piles to anchor the end of a submarine pipeline, for delivery to a production platform.

listedValue.label: Submerged Pingo
listedValue.definition: A hill of soil-covered ice pushed up by hydrostatic pressure in an area of permafrost that is located underwater.

listedValue.label: Remains of Platform
listedValue.definition: The distributed remains of a platform.

listedValue.label: Scientific Instrument
listedValue.definition: An instrument used for scientific purposes.

listedValue.label: Underwater Turbine
listedValue.definition: Any of various machines having a rotor, usually with vanes or blades, driven by the pressure, momentum, or reactive thrust of a moving fluid, as steam, water, hot gases, or air, either occurring in the form of free jets or as a fluid passing through and entirely filling a housing around the rotor and is located underwater.

listedValue.label: Active Submarine Volcano
listedValue.definition: An active seabed volcano, which may be submerged or projecting above the water at the chart sounding datum.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Offshore Platform
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of an offshore raised structure.

listedValue.label: Oil Rig
listedValue.definition: A temporary mobile structure, either fixed or floating, used in the exploration stages of oil and gas fields.

listedValue.label: Production Platform
listedValue.definition: A term used to indicate a permanent offshore structure equipped to control the flow of oil or gas. It does not include entirely submarine structures.

listedValue.label: Observation/Research Platform
listedValue.definition: A platform from which one's surroundings or events can be observed, noted or recorded such as for scientific study.

listedValue.label: Articulated Loading Platform
listedValue.definition: A metal lattice tower, buoyant at one end and attached at the other by a universal joint to a concrete filled base on the sea bed. The platform may be fitted with a helicopter platform, emergency accommodation and hawser/hose retrieval.

listedValue.label: Single Anchor Leg Mooring
listedValue.definition: A rigid frame or tube with a buoyancy device at its upper end , secured at its lower end to a universal joint on a large steel or concrete base resting on the sea bed, and at its upper end to a mooring buoy by a chain or wire.

listedValue.label: Mooring Tower
listedValue.definition: A platform secured to the sea bed and surmounted by a turntable to which ships moor.

listedValue.label: Artificial Island
listedValue.definition: A man-made structure usually built for the exploration or exploitation of marine resources, marine scientific research, tidal observations, etc.

listedValue.label: Floating Production, Storage and Off-Loading Vessel
listedValue.definition: An offshore oil/gas facility consisting of a moored tanker/barge by which the product is extracted, stored and exported.

listedValue.label: Accommodation Platform
listedValue.definition: A platform used primarily for eating, sleeping and recreation purposes.

listedValue.label: Navigation, Communication and Control Buoy
listedValue.definition: A floating structure with control room, power and storage facilities, attached to the sea bed by a flexible pipeline and cables.

listedValue.label: Floating Oil Tank
listedValue.definition: A floating structure, anchored to the seabed, for storing oil.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Offshore Production Area
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of an area at sea within which there are production facilities.

listedValue.label: Wind Farm
listedValue.definition: A collection of wind turbines that are collocated and are organized as a single power generation unit.

listedValue.label: Wave Farm
listedValue.definition: A collection of collocated devices which harness wave energy and are organized as a single power generation unit.

listedValue.label: Current Farm
listedValue.definition: A collection of collocated devices which harness tidal energy and are organized as a single power generation unit.

listedValue.label: Tank Farm
listedValue.definition: A collection of collocated large-capacity tanks in which petroleum, natural gas, or liquid petrochemicals are stored.

listedValue.label: Seabed Material Extraction Area
listedValue.definition: An area in which materials forming, or under, the seabed are removed.

listedValue.label: Solar Farm
listedValue.definition: A large-scale photovoltaic system (PV system) designed for the supply of merchant power into the electricity grid. They are differentiated from most building-mounted and other decentralised solar power applications because they supply power at the utility level, rather than to a local user or users. The generic expression utility-scale solar is sometimes used to describe this type of project.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Oil Barrier
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of barriers used to prevent the unwanted spread of oil across the sea surface.

listedValue.label: Oil Retention (High Pressure Pipe)
listedValue.definition: A pipe with holes from which air blows. When the air bubbles reach the surface they form a barrier which prevents the spread of oil.

listedValue.label: Floating Oil Barrier
listedValue.definition: A floating tube shaped structure, with a curtain (2 metre) hanging under it, below the surface, which prevents the spread of oil.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Pile
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of pile, driven into the earth as a foundation or support for a structure.

listedValue.label: Stake
listedValue.definition: An elongated wood or metal pole embedded in the seabed to serve as a marker or support.

listedValue.label: Post
listedValue.definition: A vertical piece of timber, metal or concrete forced into the earth or sea bed.

listedValue.label: Tripodal
listedValue.definition: A single structure comprising 3 or more piles held together (sections of heavy timber, steel or concrete), and forced into the earth or sea bed.

listedValue.label: Piling
listedValue.definition: A number of piles, usually in a straight line, and usually connected or bolted together.

listedValue.label: Area of Piles
listedValue.definition: A number of piles, usually in a straight line, but not connected by structural members.

listedValue.label: Pipe
listedValue.definition: A vertical hollow cylinder of metal, wood, or other material forced into the earth or seabed.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Pilot Boarding Place
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of pilot boarding method.

listedValue.label: Boarding by Pilot-Cruising Vessel
listedValue.definition: Pilot boards from a cruising vessel.

listedValue.label: Boarding by Helicopter
listedValue.definition: Pilot boards by helicopter which comes out from the shore.

listedValue.label: Pilot Comes Out from Shore
listedValue.definition: Pilot embarks from a vessel or disembarks on a vessel which comes out from the shore on request.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Pipeline/Pipe
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of a pipe systems use.

listedValue.label: Outfall Pipe
listedValue.definition: A pipe (generally a sewer or drainage pipe) discharging into the sea or a river.

listedValue.label: Intake Pipe
listedValue.definition: A pipe taking water from a river or other body of water, to drive a mill or supply a canal, waterworks, etc.

listedValue.label: Sewer
listedValue.definition: A pipe in a sewage system for carrying water or sewage to a disposal area.

listedValue.label: Bubbler System
listedValue.definition: A submerged pipe from which warm water bubbles, preventing the surrounding water from freezing.

listedValue.label: Supply Pipe
listedValue.definition: A pipe used for transport (supply) of gas or liquid product.

listedValue.label: Bubble Curtain
listedValue.definition: A high pressure sub-surface pipeline (usually on the sea floor) with holes emitting a curtain of air bubbles. Its uses include: the prevention of acoustic transmission through the water; preventing the spread of surface debris or floating liquids; controlling the movement of fish.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Preference
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The selection of a first choice compared to other options.

listedValue.label: Primary
listedValue.definition: The preferred first choice used in normal conditions.

listedValue.label: Alternate
listedValue.definition: The preferred choice in extraordinary conditions.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Production Area
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of an area set aside for heavy industry.

listedValue.label: Quarry
listedValue.definition: An open-air excavation for the extraction of stone intended principally for use in construction.

listedValue.label: Mine
listedValue.definition: An excavation made in the terrain for the purpose of extracting and/or exploiting natural resources.

listedValue.label: Stockpile
listedValue.definition: A reserve stock of material, equipment or other supplies.

listedValue.label: Power Station Area
listedValue.definition: A facility including one or more buildings and equipment used for power generation.

listedValue.label: Refinery Area
listedValue.definition: A facility where petroleum and/or petroleum products are refined.

listedValue.label: Timber Yard
listedValue.definition: An open tract for the storage of wooden lumber and timbers.

listedValue.label: Factory Area
listedValue.definition: A group of buildings where goods are manufactured.

listedValue.label: Tank Farm
listedValue.definition: A collection of collocated large-capacity tanks in which petroleum, natural gas, or liquid petrochemicals are stored.

listedValue.label: Wind Farm
listedValue.definition: A collection of wind turbines that are collocated and are organized as a single power generation unit.

listedValue.label: Slag Heap/Spoil Heap
listedValue.definition: Hill of refuse from a mine, industrial plant etc. on land.

listedValue.label: Production Plant
listedValue.definition: A plant where production takes place.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Pylon
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of the pylon based on the service it is supporting.

listedValue.label: Power Transmission Pylon/Pole
listedValue.definition: A pylon or pole that supports one or more power lines.

listedValue.label: Telephone/Telegraph Pylon/Pole
listedValue.definition: A pylon or pole that supports one or more communication lines.

listedValue.label: Aerial Cableway Pylon
listedValue.definition: A tower or pylon supporting steel cables which convey cars, buckets, or other suspended carrier units.

listedValue.label: Bridge Pylon/Tower
listedValue.definition: A tower and/or pylon from which the deck of a bridge is suspended.

listedValue.label: Bridge Pier
listedValue.definition: A pillar or abutment that supports a bridge span.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Radar Station
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of radar station based on the services offered.

listedValue.label: Radar Surveillance Station
listedValue.definition: A radar station established for traffic surveillance.

listedValue.label: Coast Radar Station
listedValue.definition: A shore-based station which the mariner can contact by radio to obtain a position.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Radar Transponder Beacon
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of radar transponder beacon based on functionality.

listedValue.label: Ramark, Radar Beacon Transmitting Continuously
listedValue.definition: A radar marker beacon which continuously transmits a signal appearing as a radial line on a radar screen, the line indicating the direction of the beacon. Ramarks are intended primarily for marine use. The name 'ramark' is derived from the words radar marker.

listedValue.label: Racon, Radar Transponder Beacon
listedValue.definition: A radar beacon which returns a coded signal which provides identification of the beacon, as well as range and bearing. The range and bearing are indicated by the location of the first character received on the radar screen. The name 'racon' is derived from the words radar beacon.

listedValue.label: Leading Racon/Radar Transponder Beacon
listedValue.definition: A radar beacon that may be used (in conjunction with at least one other radar beacon) to indicate a leading line.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Radio Station
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of radio services offered by a radio station.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: A radiobeacon is a radio transmitter which emits a distinctive or characteristic signal on which a bearing may be taken.

listedValue.label: Radio Direction-Finding Station
listedValue.definition: A radio station intended to determine only the direction of other stations by means of transmission from the latter.

listedValue.label: Differential GNSS
listedValue.definition: A radiobeacon transmitting DGPS correction signals.

listedValue.label: Toran
listedValue.definition: An electronic position fixing system used mainly by aircraft.

listedValue.label: Chaika
listedValue.definition: Chaika is a low frequency electronic position fixing system using pulsed transmissions at 100 Khz.

listedValue.label: Radio Telephone Station
listedValue.definition: The equipment needed at one station to carry on two way voice communication by radio waves only.

listedValue.label: AIS Base Station
listedValue.definition: An onshore AIS unit that monitors traffic in the waterways.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Rescue Station
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of aid station based on life saving equipment.

listedValue.label: Rescue Station with Lifeboat
listedValue.definition: A place where equipment for saving life at sea is maintained; the type of lifeboat may vary from fast, long distance boats to inflatable inshore boats.

listedValue.label: Rescue Station with Rocket
listedValue.definition: A life saving station equipped with line-carrying rocket apparatus.

listedValue.label: Refuge for Shipwrecked Mariners
listedValue.definition: Shelter or protection from danger or distress at sea.

listedValue.label: Refuge for Intertidal Area Walkers
listedValue.definition: Shelter or protection from danger in areas exposed to extreme and sudden tides or tidal streams.

listedValue.label: Lifeboat Lying at a Mooring
listedValue.definition: A place where a lifeboat is moored ready for use.

listedValue.label: Aid Radio Station
listedValue.definition: A radio station reserved for emergency situations; might also be a public telephone.

listedValue.label: First Aid Equipment
listedValue.definition: A place where first aid equipment is available.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Restricted Area
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The official legal status of each kind of restricted area defines the kind of restriction(s), for example the restriction for a 'game reserve' may be 'entering prohibited'.

listedValue.label: Offshore Safety Zone
listedValue.definition: The area around an offshore installation within which vessels are prohibited from entering without permission. Special regulations protect installations within a safety zone and vessels of all nationalities are required to respect the zone.

listedValue.label: Nature Reserve
listedValue.definition: A tract of land or water managed so as to preserve its flora, fauna, physical features, etc.

listedValue.label: Bird Sanctuary
listedValue.definition: A place where birds are bred and protected.

listedValue.label: Game Reserve
listedValue.definition: A place where wild animals or birds hunted for sport or food are kept undisturbed for private use.

listedValue.label: Seal Sanctuary
listedValue.definition: A place where seals are protected.

listedValue.label: Degaussing Range
listedValue.definition: An area, usually about two cables diameter, within which ships' magnetic fields may be measured; sensing instruments and cables are installed on the sea bed in the range and there are cables leading from the range to a control position ashore.

listedValue.label: Military Area
listedValue.definition: An area controlled by the military in which restrictions may apply.

listedValue.label: Historic Wreck Area
listedValue.definition: An area around certain wrecks of historical importance to protect the wrecks from unauthorized interference by diving, salvage or deposition (including anchoring).

listedValue.label: Navigational Aid Safety Zone
listedValue.definition: An area around a navigational aid which vessels are prohibited from entering.

listedValue.label: Minefield
listedValue.definition: An area laid and maintained with explosive mines for defence or practice purposes.

listedValue.label: Swimming Area
listedValue.definition: An area in which people may swim and therefore vessel movement may be restricted.

listedValue.label: Waiting Area
listedValue.definition: An area reserved for vessels waiting to enter a harbour.

listedValue.label: Research Area
listedValue.definition: An area where marine research takes place.

listedValue.label: Dredging Area
listedValue.definition: An area where dredging is taking place.

listedValue.label: Fish Sanctuary
listedValue.definition: A place where fish (including shellfish and crustaceans) are protected.

listedValue.label: Ecological Reserve
listedValue.definition: A tract of land managed so as to preserve the relation of plants and living creatures to each other and to their surroundings.

listedValue.label: No Wake Area
listedValue.definition: An area in which a vessels' speed must be reduced in order to reduce the size of the wake it produces.

listedValue.label: Swinging Area
listedValue.definition: An area where vessels turn.

listedValue.label: Environmentally Sensitive Sea Area
listedValue.definition: A generic term which may be used to describe a wide range of areas, considered sensitive for a variety of environmental reasons.

listedValue.label: Particularly Sensitive Sea Area
listedValue.definition: An area that needs special protection through action by IMO because of its significance for regional ecological, socio-economic or scientific reasons and because it may be vulnerable to damage by international shipping activities.

listedValue.label: Disengagement Area
listedValue.definition: An area near a fairway where vessels can go to clear the way or make an about turn and possibly return to a waiting area when nautical conditions impose it.

listedValue.label: Port Security Area
listedValue.definition: An area in which defence, law and treaty enforcement, and counter-terrorism activities that fall within the port and maritime domain apply.

listedValue.label: Coral Sanctuary
listedValue.definition: A place where coral is protected.

listedValue.label: Recreation Area
listedValue.definition: An area within which recreational activities regularly take place and therefore vessel movement may be restricted.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Road
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of a road based on size.

listedValue.label: Motorway
listedValue.definition: A limited access dual carriageway road specially designed for fast long-distance traffic and subject to special regulations concerning its use. It may have more than two lanes.

listedValue.label: Major Road
listedValue.definition: A hard surfaced (metalled) road; a main through route.

listedValue.label: Minor Road
listedValue.definition: A secondary road for local traffic.

listedValue.label: Track/Path
listedValue.definition: Track - a rough path or way formed by use. Path - a way or track laid down for walking or made by continual treading.

listedValue.label: Major Street
listedValue.definition: A main road, in an urban area, for through traffic.

listedValue.label: Minor Street
listedValue.definition: A secondary road, in an urban area, for local traffic.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Runway
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of runway based on primary aircraft type.

listedValue.label: Aeroplane Runway
listedValue.definition: A level stretch of land where aeroplanes take off and land.

listedValue.label: Helicopter Landing Pad
listedValue.definition: A site on which helicopters may land and take off.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Schedule
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The type of schedule, for instance opening, closure, etc.

listedValue.label: Normal Operation
listedValue.definition: The service, office, is open, fully manned, and operating normally, or the area is accessible as usual.

listedValue.label: Closure
listedValue.definition: The service, office, or area is closed.

listedValue.label: Unmanned Operation
listedValue.definition: The service is available but not manned.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Category of Sea Area
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of an area based on its physical characteristics.

listedValue.label: Gat
listedValue.definition: A natural or artificial passage or channel through shoals or steep banks, or across a line of banks lying between two channels.

listedValue.label: Bank
listedValue.definition: An elevation of the seafloor, at depths generally less than 200 m, but sufficient for safe surface navigation, commonly found on the continental shelf or near an island.

listedValue.label: Deep
listedValue.definition: In oceanography, an obsolete term which was generally restricted to depths greater than 6,000 m.

listedValue.label: Bay
listedValue.definition: A wide indentation in the coastline generally smaller than a gulf and larger than a cove. For the purposes of the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea, a bay is a well-marked indentation whose penetration is in such proportion to the width of its mouth as to contain land locked waters and constitute more than a mere curvature of the coast.

listedValue.label: Trench
listedValue.definition: A long, deep, asymmetrical depression with relatively steep sides, that is associated with subduction.

listedValue.label: Basin
listedValue.definition: A depression of the sea floor more or less equidimensional in plan and of variable extent.

listedValue.label: Mud Flats
listedValue.definition: A level tract of land, as the bed of a dry lake or an area frequently uncovered at low tide. Usually in plural.

listedValue.label: Reef
listedValue.definition: A shallow elevation composed of consolidated material that may constitute a hazard to surface navigation.

listedValue.label: Ledge
listedValue.definition: A rocky formation continuous with and fringing the shore.

listedValue.label: Canyon
listedValue.definition: An elongated, narrow, steep-sided depression that generally deepens down-slope.

listedValue.label: Narrows
listedValue.definition: A navigable narrow part of a bay, strait, river, etc.

listedValue.label: Shoal
listedValue.definition: A shallow elevation composed of unconsolidated material that may constitute a hazard to surface navigation.

listedValue.label: Knoll
listedValue.definition: A distinct elevation with a rounded profile less than 1000m above the surrounding relief as measured from the deepest isobath that surrounds most of the feature.

listedValue.label: Ridge
listedValue.definition: An elongated elevation of varying complexity and size, generally having steep sides.

listedValue.label: Seamount
listedValue.definition: A distinct generally equidimensional elevation greater than 1000m above the surrounding relief as measured from the deepest isobath that surrounds most of the feature.

listedValue.label: Pinnacle
listedValue.definition: Any high tower or spire-shaped pillar or rock or coral, alone or cresting a summit. It may extend above the surface of the water. It may or may not be a hazard to surface navigation.

listedValue.label: Abyssal Plain
listedValue.definition: An extensive, flat, gently sloping or nearly level region at abyssal depths.

listedValue.label: Plateau
listedValue.definition: A large, relatively flat elevation that is higher than the surrounding relief with one or more relatively steep sides.

listedValue.label: Spur
listedValue.definition: A subordinate ridge protruding from a larger feature.

listedValue.label: Shelf
listedValue.definition: The flat or gently sloping region adjacent to a continent or around an island that extends from the low water line to a depth, generally about 200m, where there is a marked increase in downward slope.

listedValue.label: Trough
listedValue.definition: A long depression generally wide and flat bottomed with symmetrical and parallel sides.

listedValue.label: Saddle
listedValue.definition: A broad pass or col in a ridge, rise or other elevation.

listedValue.label: Abyssal Hills
listedValue.definition: A tract, on occasion extensive, of low (100 - 500m) elevations on the deep sea floor.

listedValue.label: Apron
listedValue.definition: A gently dipping slope, with a smooth surface, commonly found around groups of islands and seamounts.

listedValue.label: Archipelagic Apron
listedValue.definition: A gentle slope with a generally smooth surface of the sea floor, characteristically found around groups of islands or seamounts.

listedValue.label: Borderland
listedValue.definition: A region adjacent to a continent, normally occupied by or bordering a shelf and sometimes emerging as islands, that is irregular or blocky in plan or profile, with depths well in excess of those typical of a shelf.

listedValue.label: Continental Margin
listedValue.definition: The zone, generally consisting of shelf, slope and rise, separating the continent from the deep sea floor or abyssal plain.

listedValue.label: Continental Rise
listedValue.definition: A gentle slope rising from the oceanic depths towards the foot of a continental slope.

listedValue.label: Escarpment
listedValue.definition: An elongated, characteristically linear, steep slope separating horizontal or gently sloping areas of the seafloor.

listedValue.label: Fan
listedValue.definition: A relatively smooth, depositional feature continuously deepening away from a sediment source commonly located at the lower termination of a canyon or canyon system.

listedValue.label: Fracture Zone
listedValue.definition: A long narrow zone of irregular topography formed by the movement of tectonic plates associated with an offset of a spreading ridge axis, characterized by steep-sided and/or asymmetrical ridges, troughs or escarpments.

listedValue.label: Gap
listedValue.definition: A narrow break in a ridge, rise or other elevation.

listedValue.label: Guyot
listedValue.definition: A seamount having a comparatively smooth flat top.

listedValue.label: Hill
listedValue.definition: [1] A small isolated elevation, smaller than a mountain. [2] A distinct elevation generally of irregular shape, less than 1000m above the surrounding relief as measured from the deepest isobath that surrounds most of the feature.

listedValue.label: Hole
listedValue.definition: A depression of limited extent with all sides rising steeply from a relatively flat bottom.

listedValue.label: Levee
listedValue.definition: A depositional embankment bordering a canyon, valley or sea channel.

listedValue.label: Median Valley
listedValue.definition: The axial depression of the mid-oceanic ridge system.

listedValue.label: Moat
listedValue.definition: An annular or partially annular depression commonly located at the base of seamounts, islands and other isolated elevations.

listedValue.label: Mountains
listedValue.definition: A natural elevation of the earth's surface rising more or less abruptly from the surrounding level, and attaining an altitude which, relatively to adjacent elevations, is impressive or notable.

listedValue.label: Peak
listedValue.definition: A conical or pointed elevation on a larger feature such as a seamount.

listedValue.label: Province
listedValue.definition: A geographically distinct region with a number of shared physiographic characteristics that contrast with those in the surrounding areas. This term should be modified with the generic term that best describes the majority of features in the region, for example "Seamount" in Baja California Seamount Province.

listedValue.label: Rise
listedValue.definition: A broad elevation that generally rises gently and smoothly from the surrounding relief.

listedValue.label: Sea Channel
listedValue.definition: An elongated, meandering depression, usually occurring on a gently sloping plain or fan.

listedValue.label: Seamount Chain
listedValue.definition: Several seamounts in linear or arcuate alignment. Also called: seamounts.

listedValue.label: Shelf-Edge
listedValue.definition: The line along which there is a marked increase in slope at the seaward margin of a shelf. Also called shelf break.

listedValue.label: Sill
listedValue.definition: A relatively shallow barrier between BASINS that may inhibit water movement.

listedValue.label: Slope
listedValue.definition: The sloping region that deepens from a shelf to the point where there is a general decrease in gradient.

listedValue.label: Terrace
listedValue.definition: A flat or gently sloping region, generally long and narrow, bounded along one edge by a steeper descending slope and along the other by a steeper ascending slope.

listedValue.label: Valley
listedValue.definition: An elongated depression that generally widens and deepens down-slope.

listedValue.label: Canal
listedValue.definition: An artificial waterway with no flow, or a controlled flow, used for navigation, or for draining or irrigating land (ditch).

listedValue.label: Lake
listedValue.definition: A large body of water entirely surrounded by land.

listedValue.label: River
