listedValue.definition: A general term for rock and rock fragments ranging in size from pebbles and gravel to boulders or large rock masses.

listedValue.label: Coal
listedValue.definition: A hard black mineral that is burned as fuel.

listedValue.label: Ore
listedValue.definition: A solid rock or mineral from which metal is obtained.

listedValue.label: Chemicals
listedValue.definition: Any substance obtained by or used in a chemical process.

listedValue.label: Drinking Water
listedValue.definition: Water that is suitable for human consumption.

listedValue.label: Milk
listedValue.definition: A white fluid secreted by female mammals as food for their young.

listedValue.label: Bauxite
listedValue.definition: A mineral from which aluminum is obtained.

listedValue.label: Coke
listedValue.definition: A solid substance obtained after gas and tar have been extracted from coal, used as a fuel.

listedValue.label: Iron Ingots
listedValue.definition: An oblong lump of cast iron metal.

listedValue.label: Salt
listedValue.definition: Sodium chloride obtained from mines or by the evaporation of sea water.

listedValue.label: Sand
listedValue.definition: Loose material consisting of small but easily distinguishable, separate grains, between 0.0625 and 2.000 millimetres in diameter.

listedValue.label: Timber
listedValue.definition: Wood prepared for use in building or carpentry.

listedValue.label: Sawdust/Wood Chips
listedValue.definition: Powdery fragments of wood made in sawing timber or coarse chips produced for use in manufacturing pressed board.

listedValue.label: Scrap Metal
listedValue.definition: Discarded metal suitable for being reprocessed.

listedValue.label: Liquefied Natural Gas
listedValue.definition: Natural gas that has been liquefied for ease of transport by cooling the gas to -162 Celsius.

listedValue.label: Liquefied Petroleum Gas
listedValue.definition: A compressed gas consisting of flammable light hydrocarbons and derived from petroleum.

listedValue.label: Wine
listedValue.definition: The fermented juice of grapes.

listedValue.label: Cement
listedValue.definition: A substance made of powdered lime and clay, mixed with water.

listedValue.label: Grain
listedValue.definition: A small hard seed, especially that of any cereal plant such as wheat, rice, corn, rye etc.

listedValue.label: Electricity
listedValue.definition: Electric charge or current.

listedValue.label: Ice
listedValue.definition: The solid form of water.

listedValue.label: Clay
listedValue.definition: (Particles of less than 0.002mm); stiff, sticky earth that becomes hard when baked.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Quality of Horizontal Measurement
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The degree of reliability attributed to a position.

listedValue.label: Surveyed
listedValue.definition: The position(s) was(were) determined by the operation of making measurements for determining the relative position of points on, above or beneath the earth's surface. Survey implies a regular, controlled survey of any date.

listedValue.label: Unsurveyed
listedValue.definition: Survey data is does not exist or is very poor.

listedValue.label: Inadequately Surveyed
listedValue.definition: Not surveyed to modern standards; or due to its age, scale, or positional or vertical uncertainties is not suitable to the type of navigation expected in the area.

listedValue.label: Approximate
listedValue.definition: A position that is considered to be less than third-order accuracy, but is generally considered to be within 30.5 metres of its correct geographic location. Also may apply to an object whose position does not remain fixed.

listedValue.label: Position Doubtful
listedValue.definition: Of uncertain position. The expression is used principally on charts to indicate that a wreck, shoal, etc., has been reported in various positions and not definitely determined in any.

listedValue.label: Unreliable
listedValue.definition: A feature's position has been obtained from questionable or unreliable data.

listedValue.label: Estimated
listedValue.definition: The most probable position of an object determined from incomplete data or data of questionable accuracy.

listedValue.label: Precisely Known
listedValue.definition: A position that is of a known value, such as the position of an anchor berth or other defined object.

listedValue.label: Calculated
listedValue.definition: A position that is computed from data.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Quality of Vertical Measurement
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The reliability of the value of a sounding.

listedValue.label: Depth Known
listedValue.definition: The depth from the chart datum to the seabed (or to the top of a drying feature) is known.

listedValue.label: Depth or Least Depth Unknown
listedValue.definition: The depth from chart datum to the seabed, or the shoalest depth of the feature is unknown.

listedValue.label: Doubtful Sounding
listedValue.definition: A depth that may be less than indicated.

listedValue.label: Unreliable Sounding
listedValue.definition: A depth that is considered to be an unreliable value.

listedValue.label: Least Depth Known
listedValue.definition: The shoalest depth over a feature is of known value.

listedValue.label: Least Depth Unknown, Safe Clearance at Value Shown
listedValue.definition: The least depth over a feature is unknown, but there is considered to be safe clearance at this depth.

listedValue.label: Value Reported (Not Surveyed)
listedValue.definition: Depth value obtained from a report, but not fully surveyed.

listedValue.label: Value Reported (Not Confirmed)
listedValue.definition: Depth value obtained from a report, which it has not been possible to confirm.

listedValue.label: Maintained Depth
listedValue.definition: The depth at which a channel is kept by human influence, usually by dredging.

listedValue.label: Not Regularly Maintained
listedValue.definition: Depths may be altered by human influence, but will not be routinely maintained.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Radar Band
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The band code character of the electromagnetic spectrum within which radar wave lengths lie.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Radar Conspicuous
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: A feature which returns a strong radar echo.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Radius
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The vector extending from the centre to the periphery of a circular or spherical object.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Reference Location
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Information relating to the point of origin for a measured distance as indicated on a distance mark.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Reference Tide
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The reference tide to which the series of tidal stream values apply.

listedValue.label: High Water
listedValue.definition: The highest level reached at a place by the water surface in one oscillation.

listedValue.label: Low Water
listedValue.definition: The lowest level reached at a place by the water surface in one oscillation. Also called low tide.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Reference Tide Type
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The type of tide range (that is, mean spring tide, mean neap tide or mean tide) for which a set of tidal stream rates and directions apply.

listedValue.label: Springs
listedValue.definition: The tides of increased range occurring near the times of full moon and new moon.

listedValue.label: Neaps
listedValue.definition: The tides of decreased range occurring near the times of first and last quarter.

listedValue.label: Mean
listedValue.definition: The tides of mean range occurring between spring and neap tides.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Reference Year for Magnetic Variation
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The reference calendar year for magnetic variation values.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Regulation Citation
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The regulation citation for a feature.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Reported Date
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The date that the item was observed, done, or investigated.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Restriction
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The official legal statute of each kind of restricted area.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: Defines the kind of restriction(s), for example, the restriction for 'a game preserve' may be 'entry prohibited', the restriction for an 'anchoring prohibition' is 'anchoring prohibited'. The complete information about the restriction(s), actually held in handbooks or other publications, may be encoded using an Information type.

listedValue.label: Anchoring Prohibited
listedValue.definition: An area within which anchoring is not permitted.

listedValue.label: Anchoring Restricted
listedValue.definition: A specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which anchoring is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

listedValue.label: Fishing Prohibited
listedValue.definition: An area within which fishing is not permitted.

listedValue.label: Fishing Restricted
listedValue.definition: A specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which fishing is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

listedValue.label: Trawling Prohibited
listedValue.definition: An area within which trawling is not permitted.

listedValue.label: Trawling Restricted
listedValue.definition: A specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which trawling is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

listedValue.label: Entry Prohibited
listedValue.definition: An area within which navigation and/or anchoring is prohibited.

listedValue.label: Entry Restricted
listedValue.definition: A specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which navigation is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

listedValue.label: Dredging Prohibited
listedValue.definition: An area within which dredging is not permitted.

listedValue.label: Dredging Restricted
listedValue.definition: A specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which dredging is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

listedValue.label: Diving Prohibited
listedValue.definition: An area within which diving is not permitted.

listedValue.label: Diving Restricted
listedValue.definition: A specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which diving is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

listedValue.label: No Wake
listedValue.definition: Mariners must adjust the speed of their vessels to reduce the wave or wash which may cause erosion or disturb moored vessels.

listedValue.label: Area To Be Avoided
listedValue.definition: An IMO declared routeing measure comprising an area within defined limits in which either navigation is particularly hazardous or it is exceptionally important to avoid casualties and which should be avoided by all ships, or certain classes of ships.

listedValue.label: Construction Prohibited
listedValue.definition: The erection of permanent or temporary fixed structures or artificial islands is prohibited.

listedValue.label: Discharging Prohibited
listedValue.definition: An area within which discharging or dumping is prohibited.

listedValue.label: Discharging Restricted
listedValue.definition: A specified area designated by an appropriate authority, within which discharging or dumping is restricted in accordance with specified conditions.

listedValue.label: Industrial or Mineral Exploration/Development Prohibited
listedValue.definition: An area within which industrial or mineral exploration and development are prohibited.

listedValue.label: Industrial or Mineral Exploration/Development Restricted
listedValue.definition: A specified area designated by an appropriate authority, within which industrial or mineral exploration and development is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

listedValue.label: Drilling Prohibited
listedValue.definition: An area within which excavating a hole on the sea-bottom with a drill is prohibited.

listedValue.label: Drilling Restricted
listedValue.definition: A specified area designated by an appropriate authority, within which excavating a hole on the sea-bottom with a drill is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

listedValue.label: Removal of Historical Artefacts Prohibited
listedValue.definition: An area within which the removal of historical artefacts is prohibited.

listedValue.label: Cargo Transhipment (Lightening) Prohibited
listedValue.definition: An area in which cargo transhipment (lightening) is prohibited.

listedValue.label: Dragging Prohibited
listedValue.definition: An area in which the dragging of anything along the bottom, e.g. bottom trawling, is prohibited.

listedValue.label: Stopping Prohibited
listedValue.definition: An area in which a vessel is prohibited from stopping.

listedValue.label: Landing Prohibited
listedValue.definition: An area in which landing is prohibited.

listedValue.label: Speed Restricted
listedValue.definition: An area within which speed is restricted.

listedValue.label: Swimming Prohibited
listedValue.definition: An area in which swimming is prohibited.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Scale Minimum
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The minimum scale at which the feature may be used for example for ECDIS presentation.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: The modulus of the scale is indicated, that is 1:1 250 000 is encoded as 1250000.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Scale Value Maximum
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The largest scale for the range of survey scale.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: The modulus of the scale is indicated, that is 1:25 000 is encoded as 25000.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Scale Value Minimum
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The smallest scale for the range of survey scale.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: The modulus of the scale is indicated, that is 1:250 000 is encoded as 250000.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Sector Bearing
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference. Sector bearing specifies the limit of the sector.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: The values given to the common limits of adjacent sectors should be identical. The orientation of bearing is from seaward to the central object. This conforms with the method used in 'List of Lights' publications. A generic term such as 'to shore' cannot be used; a specific bearing must be encoded. Where a light sector limit is defined as 'to the shore', it should be encoded using a value that ensures that, when the limit is drawn, it will fall entirely on land.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Sector Extension
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Distance in screen millimetres (mm) by which a sector is extended from its origin.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: The sector extension is calculated by ENC production software systems.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Sector Line Length
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference. Sector line length specifies the displayed length of the line, in ground units, defining the limit of the sector.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Signal Duration
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The time occupied by a single instance of light/sound or eclipse/silence in a signal sequence.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Signal Frequency
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The frequency of a signal.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Signal Generation
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The mechanism used to generate a fog or light signal.

listedValue.label: Automatically
listedValue.definition: Signal generation is initiated by a self regulating mechanism such as a timer or light sensor.

listedValue.label: By Wave Action
listedValue.definition: The signal is generated by the motion of the sea surface such as a bell in a buoy.

listedValue.label: By Hand
listedValue.definition: The signal is generated by a manually operated mechanism such as a hand cranked siren.

listedValue.label: By Wind
listedValue.definition: The signal is generated by the motion of air such as a wind driven whistle.

listedValue.label: Radio Activated
listedValue.definition: Activated by radio signal.

listedValue.label: Call Activated
listedValue.definition: Activated by making a call to a manned station.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Signal Group
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The number of signals, the combination of signals or the morse character(s) within one period of full sequence.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Signal Period
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The time occupied by an entire cycle of intervals of light and eclipse.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Signal Status
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The indication of an element of a signal sequence being a period of light/sound or eclipse/silence.

listedValue.label: Lit/Sound
listedValue.definition: The indication of an element of a signal sequence being a period of light or sound.

listedValue.label: Eclipsed/Silent
listedValue.definition: The indication of an element of a signal sequence being a period of eclipse or silence.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Significant Features Detected
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: A statement expressing if significant features have or have not been detected in the course of a survey.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: A feature in this context is any object, whether manmade or not, projecting above the sea floor, which may be a danger for surface navigation (reference: IHO publication S-44). Significant features detected does not describe if significant features were actually detected during a hydrographic survey, but whether the survey had the capacity to detect significant features.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Size of Features Detected
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The size of detected bathymetric features in an area.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: A feature in this context is any object, whether man-made or not, projecting above the sea floor, which may be a danger for surface navigation (reference: IHO publication S-44).- least depth of detected features measured does not describe the least depth of features that were actually detected during a hydrographic survey, but the ability of the survey to detect the least depth of features with a maximum uncertainty as defined in IHO publication S-44.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Source
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The publication, document, or reference work from which information comes or is acquired.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: May be populated with the corresponding paper chart Notice to Mariners numbers, although other references are permitted.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Speed Limit
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The maximum allowed rate of travel in an area.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Speed Maximum
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Rate of motion. The terms speed and velocity are often used interchangeably, but speed is a scalar, having magnitude only, while velocity is a vector quantity, having both magnitude and direction. Speed maximum is the maximum rate of travel that can occur.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Speed Minimum
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Rate of motion. The terms speed and velocity are often used interchangeably, but speed is a scalar, having magnitude only, while velocity is a vector quantity, having both magnitude and direction. Speed minimum is the minimum rate of travel that can occur.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Station Name
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The name of the reference tide station with reference water level for tidal stream panel observations.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Station Number
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The identification number of the reference tide station with reference water level for tidal stream panel observations.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Status
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The condition of an object at a given instant in time.

listedValue.label: Permanent
listedValue.definition: Intended to last or function indefinitely.

listedValue.label: Occasional
listedValue.definition: Acting on special occasions; happening irregularly.

listedValue.label: Recommended
listedValue.definition: Presented as worthy of confidence, acceptance, use, etc.

listedValue.label: Not in Use
listedValue.definition: Use has ceased, but the facility still exists intact; disused.

listedValue.label: Periodic/Intermittent
listedValue.definition: Recurring at intervals.

listedValue.label: Reserved
listedValue.definition: Set apart for some specific use.

listedValue.label: Temporary
listedValue.definition: Meant to last only for a time.

listedValue.label: Private
listedValue.definition: Administered by an individual or corporation, rather than a State or a public body.

listedValue.label: Mandatory
listedValue.definition: Compulsory; enforced.

listedValue.label: Extinguished
listedValue.definition: No longer lit.

listedValue.label: Illuminated
listedValue.definition: Lit by floodlights, strip lights, etc.

listedValue.label: Historic
listedValue.definition: Famous in history; of historical interest.

listedValue.label: Public
listedValue.definition: Belonging to, available to, used or shared by, the community as a whole and not restricted to private use.

listedValue.label: Synchronized
listedValue.definition: Occur at a time, coincide in point of time, be contemporary or simultaneous.

listedValue.label: Watched
listedValue.definition: Looked at or observed over a period of time especially so as to be aware of any movement or change.

listedValue.label: Unwatched
listedValue.definition: Usually automatic in operation, without any permanently-stationed personnel to superintend it.

listedValue.label: Existence Doubtful
listedValue.definition: A feature that has been reported but has not been definitely determined to exist.

listedValue.label: Buoyed
listedValue.definition: Marked by buoys.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Stream Depth
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The depth below the sea surface to which the tidal stream data refers relative to the sounding datum.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Surrounding Depth
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The depth value determined for seabed around an underwater hazard of unknown depth, based on the depth of the surrounding area.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: The value for surrounding depth is determined from the attribute depth range minimum value for the surrounding encoded Depth Area. For an area feature covered by more than one depth area, the surrounding depth is determined as the depth range minimum attribute value of the deeper of the depth areas covering the feature.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Survey Authority
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The authority which was responsible for the survey.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: Encodes the name of the source survey authority. (Examples: Hydrographic Service, Royal Australian Navy; Port of Melbourne Authority.)

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Survey Type
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of the different survey types.

listedValue.label: Reconnaissance/Sketch Survey
listedValue.definition: A survey made (due to lack of time or facilities) to a lower degree of accuracy and detail than the chosen scale would normally indicate.

listedValue.label: Controlled Survey
listedValue.definition: A thorough survey usually conducted with reference to guidelines.

listedValue.label: Examination Survey
listedValue.definition: A survey principally aimed at the investigation of underwater obstructions and dangers.

listedValue.label: Passage Survey
listedValue.definition: A survey where soundings are acquired by vessels on passage.

listedValue.label: Remotely Sensed
listedValue.definition: A survey where features have been positioned and delimited using remote sensing techniques.

listedValue.label: Full Coverage
listedValue.definition: A survey achieving 100% coverage using systematic, controlled techniques providing full seafloor coverage or full coverage to a defined depth and an investigation of all contacts.

listedValue.label: Systematic Survey
listedValue.definition: A controlled survey but full coverage may not have been achieved.

listedValue.label: Non-Systematic Survey
listedValue.definition: A survey of lower quality than a full coverage and systematic survey. Such surveys may be further categorized as reconnaissance, sketch, track, passage, remotely sensed and spot-sounding surveys.

listedValue.label: Inadequately Surveyed
listedValue.definition: Not surveyed to modern standards; or due to its age, scale, or positional or vertical uncertainties is not suitable to the type of navigation expected in the area.

listedValue.label: Spot-Sounding Survey
listedValue.definition: A survey that uses a regular (for example grid) or irregular pattern of soundings obtained one at a time, and normally with very wide spacing.

listedValue.label: Acoustically Swept Survey
listedValue.definition: A controlled, systematic survey to standard accuracy; using modern survey echo sounder with sonar sweep.

listedValue.label: Mechanically Swept Survey
listedValue.definition: Swept areas where the clearance depth is accurately known but the actual seabed depth is not accurately known.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Swept Date
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The date that the area was swept by a survey.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Technique of Vertical Measurement
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Survey method used to obtain depth information.

listedValue.label: Found by Echo Sounder
listedValue.definition: The depth was determined by using an instrument that determines depth of water by measuring the time interval between emission of a sonic or ultrasonic signal and return of its echo from the bottom.

listedValue.label: Found by Side Scan Sonar
listedValue.definition: The depth was computed from a record produced by active sonar in which fixed acoustic beams are directed into the water perpendicularly to the direction of travel to scan the seabed and generate a record of the seabed configuration.

listedValue.label: Found by Multi Beam
listedValue.definition: The depth was determined by using a wide swath echo sounder that uses multiple beams to measure depths directly below and transverse to the ship's track.

listedValue.label: Found by Diver
listedValue.definition: The depth was determined by a person skilled in the practice of diving.

listedValue.label: Found by Lead Line
listedValue.definition: The depth was determined by using a line, graduated with attached marks and fastened to a sounding lead.

listedValue.label: Swept by Wire-Drag
listedValue.definition: The given area was determined to be free from navigational dangers to a certain depth by towing a buoyed wire at the desired depth by two launches, or a least depth was identified using the same technique.

listedValue.label: Swept by Vertical Acoustic System
listedValue.definition: The given area has been swept using a system comprised of multiple echo sounder transducers attached to booms deployed from the survey vessel.

listedValue.label: Found by Electromagnetic Sensor
listedValue.definition: The depth was determined by using an instrument that compares electromagnetic signals.

listedValue.label: Photogrammetry
listedValue.definition: The science or art of obtaining reliable measurements from photographs.

listedValue.label: Satellite Imagery
listedValue.definition: The depth was determined by using instruments placed aboard an artificial satellite.

listedValue.label: Found by Levelling
listedValue.definition: The depth was determined by using levelling techniques to find the elevation of the point relative to a datum.

listedValue.label: Swept by Side Scan Sonar
listedValue.definition: The given area was determined to be free from navigational dangers to a certain depth by towing a side scan sonar.

listedValue.label: Found by LIDAR
listedValue.definition: The depth was measured by using an instrument that measures distance by emitting timed pulses of laser light and measuring the time between emission and reception of the reflected pulses.

listedValue.label: Synthetic Aperture Radar
listedValue.definition: A radar with a synthetic aperture antenna which is composed of a large number of elementary transducing elements. The signals are electronically combined into a resulting signal equivalent to that of a single antenna of a given aperture in a given direction.

listedValue.label: Hyperspectral Imagery
listedValue.definition: Term used to describe the imagery derived from subdividing the electromagnetic spectrum into very narrow bandwidths. These narrow bandwidths may be combined with or subtracted from each other in various ways to form images useful in precise terrain or target analysis.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Telecommunication Identifier
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: An identifier, such as words, numbers, letters, symbols, or any combination of those used to establish a contact to a particular person, organisation or service.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Telecommunication Service
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of methods of communication over a distance by electrical, electronic, or electromagnetic means.

listedValue.label: Voice
listedValue.definition: The transfer or exchange of information by using sounds that are being made by mouth and throat when speaking.

listedValue.label: Facsimile
listedValue.definition: A system of transmitting and reproducing graphic matter (as printing or still pictures) by means of signals sent over telephone lines.

listedValue.label: SMS
listedValue.definition: Short Message Service is a form of text messaging communication on phones and mobile phones.

listedValue.label: Data
listedValue.definition: A representation of facts, concepts or instructions in a formalised manner suitable for communication, interpretation or processing.

listedValue.label: Streamed Data
listedValue.definition: Data that is constantly received by and presented to an end-user while being delivered by a provider.

listedValue.label: Telex
listedValue.definition: A system of communication in which messages are sent over long distances by using a telephone system and are printed by using a special machine (called a teletypewriter).

listedValue.label: Telegraph
listedValue.definition: An apparatus, system or process for communication at a distance by electric transmission over wire.

listedValue.label: Email
listedValue.definition: Messages and other data exchanged between individuals using computers in a network.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Text
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: A non-formatted digital text string.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: Should be used, for example, to hold the information that is for short cautionary or explanatory notes. Therefore, text populated in text must not exceed 300 characters. Text may be in English, or in a national language. No formatting of text is possible within text. If formatted text, or text strings exceeding 300 characters, is required, then an alternate concept should be used.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Text Justification
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The anchor point of a text string.

listedValue.label: Left
listedValue.definition: Of, relating to, or located on or near the side of a person or thing that is turned toward the west when the subject is facing north (opposed to right).

listedValue.label: Centred
listedValue.definition: Equidistant from all bordering or adjacent areas; situated in the centre.

listedValue.label: Right
listedValue.definition: Of, relating to, or located on or near the side of a person or thing that is turned toward the east when the subject is facing north (opposed to left).

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Text Type
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The attribute from which a text string is derived.

listedValue.label: Name
listedValue.definition: The individual name of a feature.

listedValue.label: Light Characteristic
listedValue.definition: The distinct character, such as fixed, flashing, or occulting, which is given to each light to avoid confusion with neighbouring ones.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Time of Day End
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The time corresponding to the end of an active period.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: The time of day end must be encoded using 2 digits for the hour (hh), 2 digits for the minutes(mm) and 2 digits for the seconds (ss). This conforms to ISO 8601:2004.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Time of Day Start
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The time corresponding to the start of an active period.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: The time of day start must be encoded using 2 digits for the hour (hh), 2 digits for the minutes(mm) and 2 digits for the seconds (ss). This conforms to ISO 8601:2004.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Time Relative to Tide
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The time difference relative to the reference tide.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: Positive values are time after the referenced tide, negative values are time before the referenced tide.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Topmark/Daymark Shape
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The shape a topmark or daymark exhibits.

listedValue.label: Cone (Point Up)
listedValue.definition: Is where the vertex points up. A cone is a solid figure generated by straight lines drawn from a fixed point (the vertex) to a circle in a plane not containing the vertex. Cones are commonly used as International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmarks, lateral.

listedValue.label: Cone (Point Down)
listedValue.definition: Is where the vertex points down. A cone is a solid figure generated by straight lines drawn from a fixed point (the vertex) to a circle in a plane not containing the vertex. Cones are commonly used as International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmarks, lateral.

listedValue.label: Sphere
listedValue.definition: A curved surface all points of which are equidistant from a fixed point within, called the centre.

listedValue.label: 2 Spheres
listedValue.definition: Two spheres, one above the other. Two black spheres are commonly used as an International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmark (isolated danger).

listedValue.label: Cylinder
listedValue.definition: A solid geometrical figure generated by straight lines fixed in direction and describing with one of point a closed curve, especially a circle (in which case the figure is circular cylinder, it's ends being parallel circles). Cylinders are commonly used as International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmarks lateral.

listedValue.label: Board
listedValue.definition: Usually of rectangular shape, made from timber or metal and used to provide a contrast with the natural background of a daymark. The actual daymark is often painted on to this board.

listedValue.label: X-Shaped
listedValue.definition: Having a shape or a cross-section like the capital letter X. An x-shape as an International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmark should be 3 dimensional in shape. It is made of at least three crossed bars.

listedValue.label: Upright Cross
listedValue.definition: A cross with one vertical member and one horizontal member; that is, similar in shape to the character '+'.

listedValue.label: Cube (Point Up)
listedValue.definition: A cube standing on one of its vertexes. A cube is a solid contained by six equal squares, a regular hexahedron.

listedValue.label: 2 Cones (Point to Point)
listedValue.definition: 2 cones, one above the other, with their vertices together in the centre.

listedValue.label: 2 Cones (Base to Base)
listedValue.definition: 2 cones, one above the other, with their bases together in the centre and their vertices pointing up and down.

listedValue.label: Rhombus
listedValue.definition: A plane figure having four equal sides and equal opposite angles (two acute and two obtuse); an oblique equilateral parallelogram.

listedValue.label: 2 Cones (Points Upward)
listedValue.definition: 2 cones, one above the other, with their vertices pointing up.

listedValue.label: 2 Cones (Points Downward)
listedValue.definition: 2 cones, one above the other, with their vertices pointing down.

listedValue.label: Besom (Point Up)
listedValue.definition: Besom: A bundle of rods or twigs. Perch: A staff placed on top of a buoy, rock or shoal as a mark for navigation. A besom, point up is where the thicker (untied) end of the besom is at the bottom.

listedValue.label: Besom (Point Down)
listedValue.definition: Besom: A bundle of rods or twigs. Perch: A staff placed on top of a buoy, rock or shoal as a mark for navigation. A besom, point down is where the thinner (tied) end of the besom is at the bottom.

listedValue.label: Flag
listedValue.definition: A flag mounted on a short pole.

listedValue.label: Sphere Over a Rhombus
listedValue.definition: A sphere located above a rhombus.

listedValue.label: Square
listedValue.definition: A plane figure with four right angles and four equal straight sides.

listedValue.label: Rectangle (Horizontal)
listedValue.definition: Where the two longer opposite sides are standing horizontally. A rectangle is a plane figure with four right angles and four straight sides, opposite sides being parallel and equal in length.

listedValue.label: Rectangle (Vertical)
listedValue.definition: Where the two longer opposite sides are standing vertically. A rectangle is a plane figure with four right angles and four straight sides, opposite sides being parallel and equal in length.

listedValue.label: Trapezium (Up)
listedValue.definition: A quadrilateral having one pair of opposite sides parallel, and which stands on its longer parallel side.

listedValue.label: Trapezium (Down)
listedValue.definition: A quadrilateral having one pair of opposite sides parallel, and which stands on its shorter parallel side.

listedValue.label: Triangle (Point Up)
listedValue.definition: A figure having three angles and three sides, and which has a vertex at the top.

listedValue.label: Triangle (Point Down)
listedValue.definition: A figure having three angles and three sides, and which has a side at the top.

listedValue.label: Circle
listedValue.definition: A perfectly round plane figure whose circumference is everywhere equidistant from its centre.

listedValue.label: Two Upright Crosses (One Over the Other)
listedValue.definition: Two upright crosses, generally vertically disposed one above the other.

listedValue.label: T-Shape
listedValue.definition: Having a shape like the capital letter T.

listedValue.label: Triangle Pointing Up Over a Circle
listedValue.definition: A triangle, vertex uppermost, located above a circle.

listedValue.label: Upright Cross Over a Circle
listedValue.definition: An upright cross located above a circle.

listedValue.label: Rhombus Over a Circle
listedValue.definition: A rhombus located above a circle.

listedValue.label: Circle Over a Triangle Pointing Up
listedValue.definition: A circle located over a triangle, vertex uppermost.

listedValue.label: Other Shape (See Shape Information)
listedValue.definition: An uncommon and/or non-standardized shape as textually described using an associated attribute.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Traffic Flow
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Direction of vessels passing a reference point.

listedValue.label: Inbound
listedValue.definition: Traffic flow in a general direction toward a port or similar destination.

listedValue.label: Outbound
listedValue.definition: Traffic flow in a general direction away from a port or similar point of origin.

listedValue.label: One-Way
listedValue.definition: Traffic flow in one general direction only.

listedValue.label: Two-Way
listedValue.definition: Traffic flow in two generally opposite directions.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Uncertainty Fixed
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The best estimate of the fixed horizontal or vertical accuracy component for positions, depths, heights, vertical distances and vertical clearances.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Uncertainty Variable Factor
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The factor to be applied to the variable component of an uncertainty equation so as to provide the best estimate of the variable horizontal or vertical accuracy component for positions, depths, heights, vertical distances and vertical clearances.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Underlying Layer
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The position of the seabed type within the layers of the seabed.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Value of Annual Change in Magnetic Variation
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The annual change in magnetic variation values.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: A positive value; that is, unsigned, indicates a change in an easterly direction and a negative value indicates a change in a westerly direction.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Value of Depth Contour
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The depth of a sea bottom contour.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: Drying contours are indicated by a negative value.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Value of Magnetic Variation
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The angle between the magnetic and geographical meridians at any place, expressed in degrees east or west to indicate the direction of magnetic north from true north.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: A positive value; that is, unsigned, indicates variation in an easterly direction and a negative value indicates variation in a westerly direction.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Value of Maximum Range
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The extreme distance at which an feature can be seen or a signal detected.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: Does not apply to lights where the 'value of nominal range' should be used.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Value of Nominal Range
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The luminous range of a light in a homogenous atmosphere in which the meteorological visibility is 10 sea miles.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Value of Sounding
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The value of the measurement of a sounding relative to the chart datum.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: A drying height is indicated by a negative value.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Vertical Clearance Value
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The vertical clearance measured from the horizontal plane towards the feature overhead.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Vertical Datum
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The reference level used for expressing the vertical measurements of points on the earth's surface. Also called datum level, reference plane, levelling datum, datum for sounding reduction, datum for heights.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.alias: VERDAT; M_VDAT; Datum Level; Reference Plane; Levelling Datum; Datum for Sounding Reduction; Datum for Heights

listedValue.label: Mean Low Water Springs
listedValue.definition: The average height of the low waters of spring tides. This level is used as a tidal datum in some areas. Also called spring low water.

listedValue.label: Mean Lower Low Water Springs
listedValue.definition: The average height of lower low water springs at a place.

listedValue.label: Mean Sea Level
listedValue.definition: The average height of the surface of the sea at a tide station for all stages of the tide over a 19-year period, usually determined from hourly height readings measured from a fixed predetermined reference level.

listedValue.label: Lowest Low Water
listedValue.definition: An arbitrary level conforming to the lowest tide observed at a place, or some what lower.

listedValue.label: Mean Low Water
listedValue.definition: The average height of all low waters at a place over a 19-year period.

listedValue.label: Lowest Low Water Springs
listedValue.definition: An arbitrary level conforming to the lowest water level observed at a place at spring tides during a period of time shorter than 19 years.

listedValue.label: Approximate Mean Low Water Springs
listedValue.definition: An arbitrary level, usually within 0.3m from that of Mean Low Water Springs (MLWS).

listedValue.label: Indian Spring Low Water
listedValue.definition: An arbitrary tidal datum approximating the level of the mean of the lower low water at spring tides. It was first used in waters surrounding India.

listedValue.label: Low Water Springs
listedValue.definition: An arbitrary level, approximating that of mean low water springs (MLWS).

listedValue.label: Approximate Lowest Astronomical Tide
listedValue.definition: An arbitrary level, usually within 0.3m from that of Lowest Astronomical Tide (LAT).

listedValue.label: Nearly Lowest Low Water
listedValue.definition: An arbitrary level approximating the lowest water level observed at a place, usually equivalent to the Indian Spring Low Water (ISLW).

listedValue.label: Mean Lower Low Water
listedValue.definition: The average height of the lower low waters at a place over a 19-year period.

listedValue.label: Low Water
listedValue.definition: The lowest level reached at a place by the water surface in one oscillation. Also called low tide.

listedValue.label: Approximate Mean Low Water
listedValue.definition: An arbitrary level, usually within 0.3m from that of Mean Low Water (MLW).

listedValue.label: Approximate Mean Lower Low Water
listedValue.definition: An arbitrary level, usually within 0.3m from that of Mean Lower Low Water (MLLW).

listedValue.label: Mean High Water
listedValue.definition: The average height of all high waters at a place over a 19-year period.

listedValue.label: Mean High Water Springs
listedValue.definition: The average height of the high waters of spring tides. Also called spring high water.

listedValue.label: High Water
listedValue.definition: The highest level reached at a place by the water surface in one oscillation.

listedValue.label: Approximate Mean Sea Level
listedValue.definition: An arbitrary level, usually within 0.3m from that of Mean Sea Level (MSL).

listedValue.label: High Water Springs
listedValue.definition: An arbitrary level, approximating that of mean high water springs (MHWS).

listedValue.label: Mean Higher High Water
listedValue.definition: The average height of higher high waters at a place over a 19-year period.

listedValue.label: Equinoctial Spring Low Water
listedValue.definition: The level of low water springs near the time of an equinox.

listedValue.label: Lowest Astronomical Tide
listedValue.definition: The lowest tide level which can be predicted to occur under average meteorological conditions and under any combination of astronomical conditions.

listedValue.label: Local Datum
listedValue.definition: An arbitrary datum defined by a local harbour authority, from which levels and tidal heights are measured by this authority.

listedValue.label: International Great Lakes Datum 1985
listedValue.definition: A vertical reference system with its zero based on the mean water level at Rimouski/Pointe-au-Pere, Quebec, over the period 1970 to 1988.

listedValue.label: Mean Water Level
listedValue.definition: The average of all hourly water levels over the available period of record.

listedValue.label: Lower Low Water Large Tide
listedValue.definition: The average of the lowest low waters, one from each of 19 years of observations.

listedValue.label: Higher High Water Large Tide
listedValue.definition: The average of the highest high waters, one from each of 19 years of observations.

listedValue.label: Nearly Highest High Water
listedValue.definition: An arbitrary level approximating the highest water level observed at a place, usually equivalent to the high water springs.

listedValue.label: Highest Astronomical Tide
listedValue.definition: The highest tidal level which can be predicted to occur under average meteorological conditions and under any combination of astronomical conditions.

listedValue.label: Baltic Sea Chart Datum 2000
listedValue.definition: The datum refers to each Baltic country's realization of the European Vertical Reference System (EVRS) with land-uplift epoch 2000, which is connected to the Normaal Amsterdams Peil (NAP).

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Vertical Length
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The total vertical length of a feature.
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.remarks: For floating objects: the vertical distance from the surface of water to the highest point of that object. For fixed objects: the vertical distance from seabed or ground to the highest point of that object. For objects on top of other objects: the vertical distance from the lowest to the highest point of that object. Vertical length measurements do not require a datum.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Vessel Class
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The classification of a vessel, normally as defined by length or gross tonnage.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Virtual AIS Aid to Navigation Type
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: A purpose of a virtual AIS Aid to Navigation.

listedValue.label: North Cardinal
listedValue.definition: Indicates that it should be passed to the north side of the aid.

listedValue.label: East Cardinal
listedValue.definition: Indicates that it should be passed to the east side of the aid.

listedValue.label: South Cardinal
listedValue.definition: Indicates that it should be passed to the south side of the aid.

listedValue.label: West Cardinal
listedValue.definition: Indicates that it should be passed to the west side of the aid.

listedValue.label: Port Lateral
listedValue.definition: Indicates the port boundary of a navigational channel or suggested route when proceeding in the conventional direction of buoyage.

listedValue.label: Starboard Lateral
listedValue.definition: Indicates the starboard boundary of a navigational channel or suggested route when proceeding in the conventional direction of buoyage.

listedValue.label: Preferred Channel to Port
listedValue.definition: At a point where a channel divides, when proceeding in the conventional direction of buoyage, the preferred channel (or primary route) is indicated by a modified port-hand lateral mark.

listedValue.label: Preferred Channel to Starboard
listedValue.definition: At a point where a channel divides, when proceeding in the conventional direction of buoyage, the preferred channel (or primary route) is indicated by a modified starboard-hand lateral mark.

listedValue.label: Isolated Danger
listedValue.definition: A mark used alone to indicate a dangerous reef or shoal. The mark may be passed on either hand.

listedValue.label: Safe Water
listedValue.definition: Indicates that there is navigable water around the mark.

listedValue.label: Special Purpose
listedValue.definition: A special purpose aid is primarily used to indicate an area or feature, the nature of which is apparent from reference to a chart, Sailing Directions or Notice to Mariners

listedValue.label: New Danger Marking
listedValue.definition: A mark used to indicate the existence of a recently identified new danger, such as a wreck.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Visual Prominence
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The extent to which a feature, either natural or artificial, is visible from seaward.

listedValue.label: Visually Conspicuous
listedValue.definition: Term applied to a feature either natural or artificial which is distinctly and notably visible from seaward.

listedValue.label: Not Visually Conspicuous
listedValue.definition: An object that may be visible from seaward, but cannot be used as a fixing mark and is not conspicuous.

listedValue.label: Prominent
listedValue.definition: Objects which are easily identifiable, but do not justify being classed as conspicuous.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Water Level Effect
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The effect of the surrounding water on an object.

listedValue.label: Partly Submerged at High Water
listedValue.definition: Partially covered and partially dry at high water.

listedValue.label: Always Dry
listedValue.definition: Not covered at high water under average meteorological conditions.

listedValue.label: Always Under Water/Submerged
listedValue.definition: Remains covered by water at all times under average meteorological conditions.

listedValue.label: Covers and Uncovers
listedValue.definition: Expression intended to indicate an area of a reef or other projection from the bottom of a body of water which periodically extends above and is submerged below the surface. Also referred to as 'dries or uncovers'.

listedValue.label: Awash
listedValue.definition: Flush with, or washed by the waves at low water under average meteorological conditions.

listedValue.label: Subject to Inundation or Flooding
listedValue.definition: An area periodically covered by flood water, excluding tidal waters.

listedValue.label: Floating
listedValue.definition: Resting or moving on the surface of a liquid without sinking.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Waterway Distance
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: [1] The distance measured from an origin of a river or canal. [2] The length of the space between two points along a waterway.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: Wave Length Value
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The distance between two successive peaks (or other points of identical phase) on an electromagnetic wave.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: CATLIT
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of different light types.

listedValue.definition: a light illuminating a sector of very narrow angle and intended to mark a direction to follow. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2778)
a light associated with other lights so as to form a leading line to be followed. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2794)
an aero light is established for aeronautical navigation and may be of higher power than marine lights and visible from well offshore. (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4, 476.1)
a light marking an obstacle which constitutes a danger to air navigation. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition 2767)
a light used to automatically determine conditions of visibility which warrant the turning on or off of a sound signal. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 1885)
a broad beam light used to illuminate a structure or area. (adapted from The Collins Dictionary)
term used with leading lights to describe the position of the light on the lead as viewed from seaward.
term used with leading lights to describe the position of the light on the lead as viewed from seaward.
term used with leading lights to describe the position of the light on the lead as viewed from seaward.
term used with leading lights to describe the position of the light on the lead as viewed from seaward.

a short range (up to 2km) type of directional light. Sodium lighting gives a yellow background to a screen on which a vertical black line will be seen by an observer on the centre line. (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4, 475.8)
a light available as a backup to a main light which will be illuminated should the main light fail.
a group of lights of identical character and almost identical position, that are disposed horizontally.
a group of lights of identical character and almost identical position, that are disposed vertically.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: OBJNAM
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The individual name of an object.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: SCAMIN
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The minimum scale at which the object may be used, e.g., for ECDIS presentation.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: STATUS
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The condition of an object at a given instant in time

listedValue.definition: intended to last or function indefinitely. (The Concise Oxford Dictionary, 7th Edition)
acting on special occasions; happening irregularly. (The Concise Oxford Dictionary, 7th Edition)
presented as worthy of confidence, acceptance, use, etc. (The Macquarie Dictionary, 1988)
no longer used for the purposes intended; disused.
recurring at intervals. (The Concise Oxford Dictionary, 7th Edition)
set apart for some specific use. (adapted from The Concise Oxford Dictionary, 7th Edition)
meant to last only for a time. (The Concise Oxford Dictionary)
not in public ownership or operation.
compulsory; enforced. (The Concise Oxford Dictionary, 7th Edition)
no longer lit.
lit by floodlights, strip lights, etc.
famous in history; of historical interest. (The Concise Oxford Dictionary, 7th Edition)
belonging to, available to, used or shared by, the community as a whole and not restricted to private use. (adapted from The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)
occur at a time, coincide in point of time, be contemporary or simultaneous. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)
an object that has been reported but has not been definitely determined to exist.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The file name of an externally referenced text file.
