S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: PERSTA
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The start of the active period for a seasonal object (e.g., a buoy).

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: MLTYLT
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The number of lights of identical character that exist as a co-located group.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: COLOUR
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The property possessed by an object of producing different sensations on the eye as a result of the way it reflects or emits light.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: SORDAT
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The production date of the source, e.g., the date of measurement.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: SIGPER
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The time occupied by an entire cycle of intervals of light and eclipse.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: SIGSEQ
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: SIGSEQ

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: SORIND
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: SORIND

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: PEREND
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The end of the active period for a seasonal object (e.g., a buoy).

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: LITCHR
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The distinct character, such as fixed, flashing, or occulting, which is given to each light to avoid confusion with neighbouring ones.

listedValue.definition: a signal light that shows continuously, in any given direction, with constant luminous intensity and colour. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2780)

a rhythmic light in which the total duration of light in a period is clearly shorter than the total duration of darkness and all the appearances of light are of equal duration. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2783)
a flashing light in which a single flash of not less than two seconds duration is regularly repeated. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2796)
a light exhibiting without interruption very rapid, regular alternations of light and darkness. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2803)
a flashing light in which flashes are repeated at a rate of not less than 80 flashes per minute but less than 160 flashes per minute.
a flashing light in which flashes are repeated at a rate of not less than 160 flashes per minute.
a light with all durations of light and darkness equal. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2779)

a rhythmic light in which the total duration of light in a period is clearly longer than the total duration of darkness and all the eclipses are of equal duration. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2801)
a quick light in which the sequence of flashes is interrupted by regularly repeated eclipses of constant and long duration. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2790)
a rhythmic light in which appearances of light of two clearly different durations are grouped to represent a character or characters in the Morse code. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2798)
a signal light that shows in any given direction, two or more colours in a regularly repeated sequence with a regular periodicity. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2770)

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: VALNMR
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The nominal range at which an object can be seen or a signal detected.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: DRVAL1
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The minimum (shoalest) value of a depth range.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: HEIGHT
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The value of the vertical distance to the highest point of the object, measured from a specified vertical datum.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: SECTR1
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: SECTR1

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: DATSTA
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The earliest date on which an object (for example a buoy) will be present.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: SECTR2
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: SECTR2

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: MARSYS
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The system of navigational buoyage a region complies with.

listedValue.definition: navigational aids conform to the International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA A system.
navigational aids conform to the International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA B system.
navigational aids do not conform to any defined system.
navigational aids conform to a defined system other than International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: EXCLIT
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The outward display of the light.

listedValue.definition: a light which is only exhibited by day.
a light which is exhibited in fog or conditions of reduced visibility.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: ORIENT
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The angular distance measured from true north to the major axis of the feature.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: CATCAN
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: Classification of an artificial waterway used for travel, drainage, or irrigation.

listedValue.definition: a canal used for navigation as part of a transport system.
a canal used to drain excess water from surrounding land.
a canal used to supply water for the purpose of irrigation.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: LITVIS
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The specific visibility of a light, with respect to the light's intensity and ease of recognition.

listedValue.definition: non-marine lights with a higher power than marine lights and visible from well off shore (often 'Aero' lights). (adapted from IHO Chart Specifications, M-4)
non-marine lights with lower power than marine lights. (Bundesamt fur Seeschiffahrt und Hydrographie, Germany)
a decrease in the apparent intensity of a light which may occur in the case of partial obstructions. (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4)
a light in a sector is intensified (i.e. has longer range than other sectors). (Bundesamt fur Seeschiffahrt und Hydrographie, Germany)
a light in a sector is unintensified (i.e. has shorter range than other sectors). (Bundesamt fur Seeschiffahrt und Hydrographie, Germany)
said of the arc of a light sector designated by its limiting bearings in which the light is not visible from seaward. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3492)
this value specifies that parts of the sector are obscured.

S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.name: SIGGRP
S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.definition: The number of signals, the combination of signals or the morse character(s) within one period of full sequence.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Directional Character
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: A directional light is a light illuminating a sector of very narrow angle and intended to mark a direction to follow.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Feature Name
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: Provides the name of an entity, defines the national language of the name, and provides the option to display the name at various system display settings.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Features Detected
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The uniform assessment of detected features.
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.remarks: A feature in this context is meant to be any object, whether man made or not, projecting above the sea floor, which may be a danger for surface navigation. (Refer IHO document S-44). Features detected does not describe if features were actually detected during a hydrographic survey, but whether the survey had the capacity to detect features.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Fixed Date Range
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: An active period of a single fixed event or occurrence, as the date range between discrete start and end dates.
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.remarks: Dates must be encoded in the format YYYYMMDD; using 4 digits for the calendar year (YYYY) and, optionally, 2 digits for the month (MM) (for example April = 04) and 2 digits for the day (DD). When no specific month and/or day is required/known, the values are replaced with dashes (-). The date range of a recurring event or occurrence must be encoded using periodicDateRange.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Frequency Pair
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: A pair of frequencies for transmitting and receiving radio signals. The shore station transmits and receives on the frequencies indicated.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Horizontal Clearance Fixed
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The horizontal clearance measured between two points for a fixed span.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Horizontal Clearance Open
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The horizontal clearance measured between two points for an opening span.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Horizontal Position Uncertainty
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The best estimate of the accuracy of a position.
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.remarks: The expected input is the maximum of the two-dimensional error. The error is assumed to be positive and negative.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Information
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: Textual information about the feature. The information may be provided as a string of text or as a file name of a single external text file that contains the text.
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.remarks: At least one of the sub-attributes file reference or text must be populated.The sub-attribute file reference is generally used for long text strings or those that require formatting, however, there is no restriction on the type of text (except for lexical level) that can be held in files referenced by sub-attribute file reference.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Light Sector
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Measured Distance Value
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The distance value indicated on a distance mark, or the distance between two measured distance marks.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Multiplicity of Features
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The number of features of identical character that exist as a colocated group.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Online Resource
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: Information about online sources from which a resource or data can be obtained.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Orientation
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: (1) The angular distance measured from true north to the major axis of the feature. (2) In ECDIS, the mode in which information on the ECDIS is being presented. Typical modes include: north-up - as shown on a nautical chart, north is at the top of the display; Ships head-up - based on the actual heading of the ship, (e.g. Ships gyrocompass); course-up display - based on the course or route being taken.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Periodic Date Range
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The active period of a recurring event or occurrence.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Radar Wave Length
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The distance between two successive peaks (or other points of identical phase) on an electromagnetic wave in the radar band of the electromagnetic spectrum.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Rhythm of Light
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The sequence of times occupied by intervals of light/sound and eclipse/silence for all light characteristics or sound signals.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Schedule by Day of Week
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The nature and timings of a daily schedule by days of the week.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Sector Characteristics
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: Describes the characteristics of a light sector.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Sector Information
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: Additional textual information about a light sector.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Sector Limit
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference. The sector limit specifies the limits of the sector In a clockwise direction around the central feature (for example a light).

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Sector Limit One
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference. Sector limit one specifies the first limit of the sector. The order of sector limit one and sector limit two is clockwise around the central feature (for example a light).

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Sector Limit Two
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference. Sector limit two specifies the second limit of the sector. The order of sector limit one and sector limit two is clockwise around the central feature (for example a light).

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Shape Information
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: Textual information about the shape of a non-standard topmark.
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.remarks: No formatting of text is possible within shape information. If formatted text is required, then an associated text file referenced by the complex attribute textual description must be used.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Signal Sequence
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The sequence of times occupied by intervals of light and eclipse for all light characteristics.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Speed
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: Rate of motion. The terms speed and velocity are often used interchangeably, but speed is a scalar, having magnitude only, while velocity is a vector quantity, having both magnitude and direction.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Surface Characteristics
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The general nature of the material of which the land surface or the seabed is composed.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Survey Date Range
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The complex attribute describes the period of the hydrographic survey, as the time between its sub-attributes.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Telecommunications
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: A means or channel of communicating at a distance by electrical or electromagnetic means such as telegraphy, telephony, or broadcasting.
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.remarks: If no value is populated for the sub-attribute telecommunication service, this means the service is by voice communication. If no value is populated for the sub-attribute telecommunication carrier, this means the service is by land line communication.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Tidal Stream Panel Values
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The direction of the flow and the tidal current rate from 6 hours before to 6 hours after high water (HW) or low water (LW) at the reference tide station, at hourly or sub-hourly intervals.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Tidal Stream Value
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: A measurement of the direction and speed of a tidal stream at a given time relative to the reference tide.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Time Intervals by Day of Week
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The regular weekly operation times of a service or schedule.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Topmark
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: A characteristic shape secured at the top of a buoy or beacon to aid in its identification.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Update Description
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The textual description of changes included in an update.
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.remarks: The sub-attribute text is populated with a brief description of the changes made when the Update is applied; for example Navigational aids inserted; Changes to depths alongside and new pontoons added.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Value of Local Magnetic Anomaly
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The value of the deviation from the normal magnetic variation.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Vertical Clearance Closed
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The vertical clearance of a feature in closed condition (for example a closed lifting bridge) measured from the horizontal plane towards the feature overhead.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Vertical Clearance Fixed
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The vertical clearance measured from the horizontal plane towards a fixed (non-opening) feature overhead.
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.remarks: Vertical clearance fixed must not be used to populate authorized safe clearances.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Vertical Clearance Open
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The vertical clearance of a feature in opened condition (for example an open lifting bridge) measured from the horizontal plane towards the feature overhead.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Vertical Clearance Safe
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The safe vertical clearance of a feature measured from the horizontal plane towards the feature overhead.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Vertical Uncertainty
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The best estimate of the vertical accuracy of depths, heights, vertical distances and vertical clearances.
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.remarks: Encodes the vertical uncertainty associated with any vertical measurement.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Vessel Speed Limit
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The maximum allowed rate of travel for a vessel in an area in knots.

S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.name: Zone of Confidence
S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.definition: The overall indication of the quality of bathymetric data within an area based on the positional accuracy, survey equipment and coverage; optionally within a specified data range.

S100_FC_Role.name: Positions
S100_FC_Role.definition: a pointer to a specific cartographically positioned location for text.

S100_FC_Role.name: Supported by
S100_FC_Role.definition: a pointer to the master feature that equipment feature(s) are supported by.

S100_FC_Role.name: Supports
S100_FC_Role.definition: a pointer to the equipment feature(s) supported by a master feature.

S100_FC_Role.name: Updates
S100_FC_Role.definition: a pointer to a feature that has been updated.

S100_FC_Role.name: Component of
S100_FC_Role.definition: a pointer to a part in a whole-part relationship.

S100_FC_Role.name: Consists of
S100_FC_Role.definition: a pointer to the aggregate in a whole-part relationship.

S100_FC_Role.name: Has auxiliary
S100_FC_Role.definition: A pointer to a feature to which incidental, secondary or supplementary features are related.

S100_FC_Role.name: Auxiliary to
S100_FC_Role.definition: A pointer to incidental, secondary or supplementary features related to the referenced feature.

S100_FC_Role.name: Information provided for
S100_FC_Role.definition: A pointer to a specific feature(s) for which further information is required.

S100_FC_Role.name: Provides information
S100_FC_Role.definition: A pointer to an object that provides more information about the referencing feature or information type.

S100_FC_Role.name: Identifies
S100_FC_Role.definition: A pointer to a specific feature(s)

S100_FC_InformationAssociation.name: Additional information
S100_FC_InformationAssociation.definition: an information association for the binding between at least one instance of a geo feature and an instance of an information type.

S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.name: Structure/equipment
S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.definition: a feature association for the binding between a navigation aid equipment feature and the structure that supports it.

S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.name: Updated information
S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.definition: a feature association for the binding between an update information feature and updated feature(s) that it identifies.

S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.name: Two-way route aggregation
S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.definition: a feature association for the binding between a two-way route and its component features.

S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.name: Aids to navigation association
S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.definition: a feature association for the binding between navigational aids and the traffic systems (such as routeing measures) that they define.

S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.name: ASL aggregation
S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.definition: a feature association for the binding between an Archipelagic Sea Lane and its component features.

S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.name: Bridge aggregation
S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.definition: feature association for the binding between a bridge and its component features.

S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.name: Caution area association
S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.definition: a feature association for the binding between a caution area and the traffic systems (such as routeing measures) to which the cautionary information applies.

S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.name: Deep Water route aggregation
S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.definition: a feature association for the binding between a Deep Water route and its component features.

S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.name: Island aggregation
S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.definition: a feature association for the binding between a named group if islands.

S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.name: Range system aggregation
S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.definition: a feature association for the binding between navigational tracks and the navigational aids that define the tracks.

S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.name: Text association
S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.definition: a feature association for the binding between a geo feature and the cartographically positioned location for text.

S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.name: Traffic Separation Scheme aggregation
S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.definition: a feature association for the binding between a Traffic Separation Scheme or a Traffic Separation Scheme System and its component features.

S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.name: Fairway aggregation
S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.definition: A feature association for the binding between related fairways comprising a fairway system.

S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.name: Fairway auxiliary
S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.definition: A feature association for the binding between a fairway and related features auxiliary to the fairway.

S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.name: Pilotage District Association
S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.definition: A feature association for the binding between a pilotage gistrict and its component pilot boarding places

S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.name: Mooring trot aggregation
S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.definition: A feature association for the binding between a mooring trot and its component parts.

S100_FC_InformationType.name: Contact Details
S100_FC_InformationType.definition: Information on how to reach a person or organisation by postal, internet, telephone, telex and radio systems.

S100_FC_InformationType.name: Service Hours
S100_FC_InformationType.definition: The time when a service is available and known exceptions.

S100_FC_InformationType.name: Non-Standard Working Day
S100_FC_InformationType.definition: Days when many services are not available. Often days of festivity or recreation or public holidays when normal working hours are limited, especially a national or religious festival, etc.

S100_FC_InformationType.name: Nautical Information
S100_FC_InformationType.definition: Nautical information about a related area or facility.

S100_FC_InformationType.name: Spatial Quality
S100_FC_InformationType.definition: The indication of the quality of the locational information for features in a dataset.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Quality of Non-Bathymetric Data
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area within which a uniform assessment of the quality of the non-bathymetric data exists.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Data Coverage
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A geographical area that describes the coverage and extent of spatial objects.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Navigational System of Marks
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area within which the navigational system of marks has been established in relation to a specific direction.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Local Direction of Buoyage
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area within which the navigational system of marks has been established in relation to a specific direction.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Quality of Bathymetric Data
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area within which a uniform assessment of the quality of the bathymetric data exists.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Sounding Datum
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: The horizontal plane or tidal datum to which soundings have been reduced. Also called datum for sounding reduction.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Vertical Datum of Data
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Any level surface (for example Mean Sea Level) taken as a surface of reference to which the elevations within a data set are reduced. Also called datum level, reference level, reference plane, levelling datum, datum for heights.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Quality of Survey
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area within which a uniform assessment of the reliability of source survey information exists.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Update Information
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Update Information metadata feature is used to represent a change to the information shown.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Magnetic Variation
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: The angle between the magnetic and geographic meridians at any place, expressed in degrees east or west to indicate the direction of magnetic north from true north. Also called magnetic declination.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Local Magnetic Anomaly
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An anomaly of the magnetic field of the Earth, extending over a relatively small area, due to local magnetic influences. Also called local attraction or magnetic anomaly.
S100_FC_FeatureType.alias: LOCMAG; Local Attraction; Magnetic Anomaly; Local Magnetic Disturbance

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Coastline
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: The line where shore and water meet. Shoreline and coastline are generally used synonymously.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Land Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: The solid portion of the Earth's surface, as opposed to sea, water.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Island Group
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A group of islands, including archipelago's.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Land Elevation
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An elevation is the vertical distance of a point or a level, on, or affixed to, the surface of the earth, measured from a specified vertical datum.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: Used to encode both spot heights and land (height) contours.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: River
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A relatively large natural stream of water.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Rapids
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Portions of a stream with accelerated current where it descends rapidly but without a break in the slope of the bed sufficient to form a waterfall. Usually used in the plural.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Waterfall
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A vertically descending part of a watercourse where it falls from a height (for example: over a rock or a precipice). In place names, commonly shortened to fall or falls, for example Niagara Falls.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Lake
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A large body of water entirely surrounded by land.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Land Region
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area of natural or cultivated scenery defined by its geographical characteristics and may be known by its proper name.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Vegetation
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Plants collectively or individually, especially those dominating a particular area or habitat.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Ice Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area of ice over land or water.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Sloping Ground
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An inclined surface.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Slope Topline
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: The upper marking of a slope, for example the ridge line or the separation line between two different gradients.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Tideway
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A channel through which a tidal current runs.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Built-Up Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area of land or construction over the water containing a concentration of buildings and/or other structures.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Building
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A free-standing self-supporting construction that is roofed, usually walled, and is intended for human occupancy (for example: a place of work or recreation) and/or habitation.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: This feature is used to encode single buildings, including those with a particular function or service of major interest.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Airport/Airfield
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A defined area on land (including any buildings, installations and equipment) intended to be used either wholly or in part for the arrival, departure and surface movement of aircraft.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Runway
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A defined rectangular area, on a land aerodrome, prepared for the landing and take-off run of aircraft, including helicopters.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Bridge
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: (1) An elevated structure extending across or over the weather deck of a vessel, or part of such a structure. The term is sometimes modified to indicate the intended use, such as navigating bridge or signal bridge. (2) A structure erected over a depression or an obstacle such as a body of water, railroad, etc., to provide a roadway for vehicles or pedestrians.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A bridge may consist of portions which cover the land and the water.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Span Fixed
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A fixed component of the deck of a bridge spanning successive bridge piers.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Span Opening
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An opening component of the deck of a bridge spanning successive bridge piers.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Conveyor
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A mechanical device for conveying bulk material or people using an endless moving belt or series of rollers.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Cable Overhead
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A single continuous rope-like bundle consisting of multiple strands of fiber, plastic, metal, and/or glass, which is supported by structures such as poles or pylons and passing over or nearby navigable waters.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: The cable supports are encoded as separate pylon/bridge support features.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Pipeline Overhead
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A string of interconnected pipes, supported by pylons and passing over or nearby navigable waters, used for the transport of matter, nowadays mainly oil or gas.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A pipeline is a string of interconnected pipes used for the transport of matter, nowadays mainly oil or gas (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3857).

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Pylon/Bridge Support
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A vertical construction consisting, for example, of a steel framework or pre-stressed concrete to carry cables, a bridge, etc.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Fence/Wall
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A man-made barrier used as an enclosure or boundary or for protection.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Railway
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A rail or set of parallel rails on which a train, tram, or rail wagon runs.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Road
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A route with a specially prepared surface that is intended for use by wheeled vehicles or pedestrians.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Tunnel
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A passage that is open to the atmosphere at both ends, buried under the sea bed or laid over the sea floor or bored under the ground or through mountains.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Landmark
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A prominent object at a fixed location on land which can be used in determining a location or a direction.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Silo/Tank
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A large storage structure used for storing loose materials, liquids and/or gases.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Wind Turbine
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A tower and associated equipment that generates electrical power from wind. They can be sited offshore and may be either fixed or floating.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Fortified Structure
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A structure that is specifically designed or reinforced to provide for defence from armed attack.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A fortified structure is often disused, decayed or used for non-defence purpose. Such structures range from major castles and forts to minor lookout posts.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Production/Storage Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area on land for the exploitation or storage of natural resources.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Checkpoint
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An official location at which to register, declare and/or inspect goods and/or people.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: The object 'checkpoint' does not include facilities such as buildings, gates or other installations.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Hulk
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: The hull of a wrecked or condemned ship, from which the fittings and superstructure have usually been removed, which is moored in a permanent position or grounded. It may be abandoned or put to some other use.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Pile
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A long heavy timber or section of steel, wood, concrete, etc., forced into the earth or sea floor to serve as a support, as for a pier, or to resist lateral pressure; or as a free standing pole within a marine environment.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Dyke
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A dyke (or dike) is an artificial embankment to contain or hold back water.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Shoreline Construction
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A fixed artificial structure in the water and/or adjoining the land. It may also refer to features such as training walls, which are not necessarily connected to, nor form part of the shoreline.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Causeway
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A raised way across low or wet ground or water.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Canal
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An artificial waterway with no flow, or a controlled flow, used for navigation, or for draining or irrigating land (ditch).

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Distance Mark
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A distance mark indicates the distance measured from an origin and consists of either a solid visible structure or a distinct location without special installation. Usually found on canals.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Gate
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A structure that may be swung, drawn, or lowered to block an entrance or passageway on a watercourse.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: Used to encode gates that control the flow of water.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Dam
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A barrier to check or confine anything in motion; particularly one constructed to hold back water and raise its level to form a reservoir, or to prevent flooding.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Crane
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A machine for lifting, shifting and lowering objects or materials by means of a swinging boom or with a lifting apparatus supported on an overhead track.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: The position of a sheerlegs or a travelling crane is defined as its resting position.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Berth
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Place in which a ship is moored at wharf.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Mooring/Warping Facility
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: The equipment or structure used to secure a vessel.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Dry Dock
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An artificial basin fitted with a gate or caisson, into which vessels can be floated and the water pumped out to expose the vessel's bottom. Also called graving dock.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Floating Dock
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A form of dry dock consisting of a floating structure of one or more sections which can be partly submerged by controlled flooding to receive a vessel, then raised by pumping out the water so that the vessel's bottom can be exposed.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Pontoon
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A floating structure, usually rectangular in shape which serves as landing, pier head, bridge support, etc.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Dock Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An artificially enclosed area within which ships may moor and which may have gates to regulate water level.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Gridiron
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A structure in the intertidal zone serving as a support for vessels at low stages of the tide to permit work on the exposed portion of the vessel's hull.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Lock Basin
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A wet dock in a waterway, permitting a ship to pass from one level to another.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Mooring Trot
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A mooring is a place where a vessel may be secured. A mooring trot is a mooring that is composed of ground tackle, mooring cables, buoys and mooring berths on junction cables.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Sea Area/Named Water Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A geographically defined part of the sea or other navigable waters. It may be specified within its limits by its proper name.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: Each sea area is defined independent of any other. Smaller sea areas may be located within larger sea areas.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Tidal Stream - Flood/Ebb
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Approximate tidal stream rates given as discrete rate values for flood and ebb flow during springs.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A tidal stream (or tidal current) is a horizontal movement of water associated with the rise and fall of the tide caused by tide-producing forces.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Current - Non-Gravitational
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Any current that is caused by other than tide producing forces.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: Non-gravitational currents include either singly or in combination: ocean currents (wind and/or density driven), inter-oceanic equalizing currents, currents of navigable rivers, river outflow effects offshore and other non-tidal flows.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Water Turbulence
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: The disturbance of water caused by the interaction of any combination of waves, currents, tidal streams, wind, shoal patches and obstructions.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Tidal Stream Panel Data
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Approximate tidal stream characteristics given as discrete value sets at a specified interval before and/or after a high or low water.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A tidal stream (or tidal current) is an alternating horizontal movement of water associated with the rise and fall of the tide caused by tide-producing forces.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Sounding
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Measured or charted depth of water (may be a drying height), or the measurement of such a depth, which has been reduced to a vertical datum.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: Drying heights (drying soundings) are indicated by a negative value.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Dredged Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area of the bottom of a body of water which has been deepened by dredging.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Swept Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area that has been determined to be clear of navigational dangers to a specified depth.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Depth Contour
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A line connecting points of equal water depth which is sometimes significantly displaced outside of soundings, symbols, and other chart detail for clarity as well as generalization. Depth contours therefore often represent an approximate location of the line of equal depth as related to the surveyed line delineated on the source.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: Drying contours are encoded with negative values.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Depth Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A water area whose depth is within a defined range of values.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: Intertidal areas are encoded as depth areas. These do not have to include soundings. The depth range within a depth area is defined by the attributes depth range maximum value and depth range minimum value.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Depth - No Bottom Found
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Upon investigation the bottom was not found at this depth.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Unsurveyed Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area where hydrographic survey data is non-existent.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Seabed Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A region of the seabed including the material of which it is composed and its physical characteristics. Also called nature of bottom, character (or characteristics) of the bottom, or quality of the bottom.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: Generally, it is not possible to define a seabed area by its real extent. For that reason, the characteristics of the seabed area may be represented at one single position.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Weed/Kelp
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Any macroscopic marine alga.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Seagrass
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Any of various submerged monocotyledonous plants (such as eelgrass, tape grass, and turtle grass) of tropical to temperate usually shallow coastal waters that have narrow grasslike leaves and often form dense underwater meadows.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Sandwave
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A large mobile wave-like sediment feature in shallow water and composed of sand. The wavelength may reach 100 metres, the amplitude may be up to 20 metres.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Spring
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A natural issue of water or other substances from the earth. One on the bottom of the sea is called a submarine spring.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Underwater/Awash Rock
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A concreted mass of stony material or coral which dries, is awash or is below the water surface.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Wreck
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: The ruined remains of a stranded or sunken vessel which has been rendered useless.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Obstruction
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: In marine navigation, anything that hinders or prevents movement, particularly anything that endangers or prevents passage of a vessel. The term is usually used to refer to an isolated danger to navigation, such as a sunken rock or pinnacle.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Foul Ground
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Areas over which it is safe to navigate but which should be avoided foranchoring, taking the ground or ground fishing.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Discoloured Water
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Unnatural coloured areas in the sea which may or may not indicate the existence of shoals.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Fishing Facility
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A structure for fishing purposes which can be an obstruction to ships in general. The position of these structures may vary frequently over time.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Marine Farm/Culture
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An assemblage of cages, nets, rafts and floats or posts where fish, including shellfish, are artificially cultivated.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Offshore Platform
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A permanent offshore structure, either fixed or floating.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Cable Submarine
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An assembly of wires or fibres, or a wire rope or chain, which has been laid underwater or buried beneath the sea floor.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Cable Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area which contains one or more submarine cables.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Pipeline Submarine/On Land
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A connected set of pipes for conveying liquids, slurries, or gases.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A pipeline is a string of interconnected pipes used for the transport of matter, nowadays mainly oil or gas (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3857). It must be assumed that the pipes are vulnerable to damage from anchoring or trawling. They may be a potential danger to navigation (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4).

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Submarine Pipeline Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area containing one or more pipelines.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Offshore Production Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area at sea within which there are production facilities.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Navigation Line
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A straight line extending towards an area of navigational interest and generally generated by two navigational aids or one navigational aid and a bearing.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: The extent of the navigation line depends on the visibility of the navigational aid(s). The recommended track is that portion of a 'navigation line' that a ship should use for navigation.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Recommended Track
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A route which has been specially examined to ensure so far as possible that it is free of dangers and along which ships are advised to navigate.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: Recommended tracks include all channels recommended for hydrographic reasons to lead safely between shoal depths. The use of such tracks is generally left to the discretion of the mariner and will depend on the vessel's draught, the state of the tide, adequacy of navigational aids and so on (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4). The recommended track is that portion of a 'navigation line' that a ship should use for navigation. In the case of a two-way recommended track only one value of orientation is encoded; the other value can be deduced (that is, the value encoded + 180 degrees).

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Range System
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Navigation system limited in their positioning capability to coastal regions, or those systems limited to making landfall

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Fairway
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: That part of a river, harbour and so on, where the main navigable channel for vessels of larger size lies. It is also the usual course followed by vessels entering or leaving harbours, called 'ship channel'.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Fairway System
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: That part of a river, harbour and so on, where the main navigable channel for vessels of larger size lies. It is also the usual course followed by vessels entering or leaving harbours, called ship channel. A fairway system is an aggregation of connected fairway features making up a complex fairway system.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A fairway system is composed of two or more Fairway features that comprise a complex fairway routeing system, for instance a long fairway comprising several bends.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Recommended Route Centreline
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A recommended route centreline indicates the 'centreline' of a recommended route.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A recommended route is a route of undefined width, for the convenience of ships in transit, which is often marked by centerline buoys (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 4448). A recommended route describes the regulation of navigation for non-hydrographic reasons such as the prevention of collision or the avoidance of pollution risks. It is generally laid down by a national or international authority other than the hydrographic authority. (IHO Chart Specifications, S-4)

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Two-Way Route Part
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area of a two-way route within which traffic flow is generally along one bearing (and possibly its reciprocal).
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: The complete two-way route consists of one or more parts depending on the shape of the two-way route. The orientation of the two-way route part is defined by its centerline and is related to the general direction of the two-way route.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Two-Way Route
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A route within defined limits inside which two way traffic is established, aimed at providing safe passage of ships through waters where navigation is difficult or dangerous.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Recommended Traffic Lane Part
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A traffic flow pattern indicating a recommended directional movement of traffic where it is impractical or unnecessary to adopt an established direction of traffic flow.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: Several Hydrographic Offices, in consultation with their Ministries of Transport, have added recommended directions in areas such as the outer approaches to major ports in order to show the best routes for crossing traffic or to minimize head-on encounters.(IHO Chart Specifications, M-4). The object 'recommended traffic lane part' indicates the recommended traffic flow, for example, between two TSS; in the entrance areas of a TSS; or beside a deep water route. The complete recommended traffic lane consists of one or more parts depending on the various shapes of the recommended traffic lane. The orientation of the recommended traffic lane part is defined by the middle-line of the recommended traffic lane part relating to the general direction of the recommended traffic lane part.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Deep Water Route Centreline
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A Deep Water route centreline indicates the centreline of a route, the width of which is not explicitly defined.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A deep water route is a route in a designated area, within defined limits, which has been accurately surveyed for clearance of sea bottom and submerged obstacles to a minimum indicated depth of water (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 1280). Additional information can be found in IHO Technical Resolution A1.17.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Deep Water Route Part
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area of a deep water route within which ships proceed in the same direction.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A deep water route is a route in a designated area, within defined limits, which has been accurately surveyed for clearance of sea bottom and submerged obstacles to a minimum indicated depth of water (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 1280). The complete deep water route consists of one or more parts depending on the shape of the deep water route. The orientation of the route part is defined by the middle line of the part relating to the general direction of the deep water route. Additional information can be found in IHO Technical Resolution A1.17.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Deep Water Route
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A route within defined limits which has been accurately surveyed for clearance of sea bottom and submerged obstacles as indicated on the chart.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A complete Deep Water route (DW) system are composed of the features Deep Water Route Centreline, Deep Water Route Part and any associated navigation aids that comprise a complex Deep Water Route system.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Inshore Traffic Zone
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A routeing measure comprising a designated area between the landward boundary of a traffic separation scheme and the adjacent coast, to be used in accordance with the provisions of the International Regulations for Preventing Collisions at Sea.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Precautionary Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A routeing measure comprising an area within defined limits where ships must navigate with particular caution and within which the direction of traffic flow may be recommended.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Traffic Separation Scheme Lane Part
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area within defined limits in which one-way traffic is established. Natural obstacles, including those forming separation zones, may constitute a boundary.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: The complete traffic lane may consist of one or more lane parts depending on the shape of the lane.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Traffic Separation Zone
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A zone separating the traffic lanes in which ships are proceeding in opposite, or nearly opposite directions; or separating a traffic lane from the adjacent sea area; or separating traffic lanes designated for particular classes of ships proceeding in the same direction.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Traffic Separation Line
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A line separating the lanes in which ships are proceeding in opposite, or nearly opposite directions; or separating a traffic lane from an adjacent sea area; or separating traffic lanes designated for particular classes of ships proceeding in the same direction.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Traffic Separation Scheme Boundary
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: The outer limit of a traffic lane part or a traffic separation scheme roundabout.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Traffic Separation Scheme Crossing
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A defined area where traffic lanes cross.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Traffic Separation Scheme Roundabout
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A routeing measure comprising a separation point or circular separation zone and a circular traffic lane within defined limits. Traffic within the roundabout is separated by moving in a counterclockwise direction around the separation point or zone.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Traffic Separation Scheme
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A routeing measure aimed at the separation of opposing streams of traffic by appropriate means and by the establishment of traffic lanes.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Archipelagic Sea Lane Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Sea lanes designated by an archipelagic State for the passage of ships and aircraft.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Archipelagic Sea Lane Axis
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: The reference line used to determine the maximum extents of an Archipelagic Sea Lane. It may not indicate the deepest water nor any recommended route or track.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: Article 53 of the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS) states that: an archipelagic State may designate sea lanes ..., suitable for the continuous and expeditious passage of foreign ships ... through ... its archipelagic waters and the adjacent Territorial Sea. ... All ships ... enjoy the right of archipelagic sea lanes passage in such sea lanes ... [which] include all normal passage routes used as routes for international navigation through archipelagic waters. (Note: references to aircraft and air routes in UNCLOS have been omitted in these extracts from Article 53).

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Archipelagic Sea Lane
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Sea lanes designated by an archipelagic State for the passage of ships and aircraft. The Archipelagic Sea Lane aggregates all component parts of an Archipelagic Sea Lane system.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Radio Calling-In Point
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A designated position at which vessels are required to report to a traffic control centre. Also called reporting point or radio reporting point.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: Radio calling-in points are established in certain busy waterways and port approaches to assist traffic control.
S100_FC_FeatureType.alias: RDOCAL; Radio Reporting Point; Reporting Point; Calling-In Point

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Ferry Route
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A route in a body of water where a ferry crosses from one shoreline to another.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Radar Line
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Recommended tracks along which ships can be guided by coastal radar stations in the event of bad visibility.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Radar Range
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Indicates the coverage of a sea area by a radar surveillance station. Inside this area a vessel may request shore-based radar assistance, particularly in poor visibility.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: Many large ports have a radar surveillance system covering their approaches to provide guidance for vessels, particularly in poor visibility. The maximum range of the system forms an arc or series of overlapping arcs (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4).

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Radar Station
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A station with a transmitter emitting pulses of ultra-high frequency radio waves which are reflected by solid objects and are detected upon their return to the sending station.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: The feature 'radar station' is used to encode the technical equipment itself independent of the building or structure where it is installed. This building or structure, for example mast, tower, building, radar dome is a different feature.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Anchorage Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area in which vessels or seaplanes anchor or may anchor.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Anchor Berth
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A designated area of water where a vessel, sea plane, etc., may anchor.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: In general the anchor berth is defined by the centre point and a swinging circle radius.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Seaplane Landing Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A designated portion of water for the landing and take-off of seaplanes.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Dumping Ground
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A sea area where dredged material or other potentially more harmful material, for example explosives, chemical waste, is deliberately deposited.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Military Practice Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area within which naval, military or aerial exercises are carried out. Also called an 'exercise area'.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Administration Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A defined area within which a jurisdiction applies. It may or may not be named.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Cargo Transhipment Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area designated for transfer of cargo from one vessel to another sometimes in order to reduce a vessels draught. Also called cargo transfer area or cargo lightening area.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: The transhipment of cargo is often known as 'lightering' and the area may be known as 'lightering area' or 'cargo transfer area'.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Caution Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Generally, an area where the mariner has to be made aware of circumstances influencing the safety of navigation.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: This may be required to identify: a danger, a risk, a rule, or advice -- which is not directly related to a specific object.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Information Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area for which general information regarding navigation, but not directly related to safety of navigation, is available.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Contiguous Zone
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A zone contiguous to a coastal States Territorial Sea, which may not extend beyond 24 nautical miles from the baselines from which the breadth of the Territorial Sea is measured. The coastal state may exercise certain control in this zone subject to the provisions of International Law.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Continental Shelf Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: The continental shelf of a coastal State comprises the sea bed and subsoil of the submarine areas that extend beyond its territorial sea throughout the natural prolongation of its land territory to the outer edge of the continental margin, or to a distance of 200 nautical miles from the baselines from which the breadth of the territorial sea is measured where the outer edge of the continental margin does not extend up to that distance.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Custom Zone
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: The area within which national custom regulations are in force.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Exclusive Economic Zone
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area, not exceeding 200 nautical miles from the baselines from which the breadth of the territorial sea is measured, subject to a specific legal regime established in the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea under which the coastal state has certain rights and jurisdiction.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Fishery Zone
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: The offshore zone in which exclusive fishing rights and management are held by the coastal nation.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: The fishery zone commonly coincides with other zones such as: Continental Shelf, Exclusive Economic Zone.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Fishing Ground
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A water area in which fishing is frequently carried on. Also called fishing area or fishing zone.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Free Port Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A port where certain import and export duties are waived (unless goods pass into the country) to facilitate reshipment to other countries.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Harbour Area (Administrative)
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: The area over which a harbour authority has jurisdiction.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Log Pond
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A maritime area enclosed with connected floating timbers used as a staging area for sawn logs.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Oil Barrier
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A floating barrier to stop and contain the spread of oil on a water body surface.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Straight Territorial Sea Baseline
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Straight baselines are a system of straight lines joining specified or discrete points on the low-water line, usually known as straight baseline turning points. Straight baselines are used in delimitation.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Territorial Sea Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A belt of water of a defined breadth but not exceeding 12 nautical miles measured seaward from the territorial sea baseline.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Submarine Transit Lane
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A lane where submarines may navigate under water or at the surface.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Pilotage District
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An area within which a pilotage direction exists. Such directions are regulated by a competent harbour authority which dictates circumstances under which they apply.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Collision Regulations Limit
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Convention on the International Regulations for Preventing Collisions at Sea, 1972 (COLREGs). The demarcation line between inland navigation rules and international navigation rules.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Marine Pollution Regulations Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: The International Convention for the Prevention of Pollution from Ships (MARPOL) is the main international convention covering prevention of pollution of the marine environment by ships from operational or accidental causes.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Restricted Area Navigational
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A specified area on land or water designated by an appropriate authority within which access or navigation is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions. A navigational restricted area is an area where the restrictions have a direct impact on the navigation of a vessel in the area.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Restricted Area Regulatory
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A specified area on land or water designated by an appropriate authority within which access or navigation is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions. A regulatory restricted area is an area where the restrictions have no direct impact on the navigation of a vessel in the area, but impact on the activities that can take place within the area.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Light All Around
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An all around light is a light that is visible over the whole horizon of interest to marine navigation and having no change in the characteristics of the light.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Light Sectored
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A light presenting different appearances (in particular, different colours) over various parts of the horizon of interest to maritime navigation.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Light Fog Detector
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A fog detector light is a light used to automatically determine conditions of visibility which warrant the turning on or off of a sound signal.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Light Air Obstruction
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An air obstruction light is a light marking an obstacle which constitutes a danger to air navigation.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Buoy Lateral
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A lateral buoy is used to indicate the port or starboard hand side of the route to be followed. They are generally used for well defined channels and are used in conjunction with a conventional direction of buoyage.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A buoy is a floating object moored to the bottom in a particular place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 565). Light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Buoy Cardinal
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A cardinal buoy is used in conjunction with the compass to indicate where the mariner may find the best navigable water. It is placed in one of the four quadrants (North, East, South and West), bounded by inter-cardinal bearings from the point marked.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A buoy is a floating object moored to the bottom in a particular place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes. (IHO Dictionary S-32 5th Edition, 565). Topmark, light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Buoy Isolated Danger
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A isolated danger buoy is a buoy moored on or above an isolated danger of limited extent, which has navigable water all around it.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A buoy is a floating object moored to the bottom in a particular place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 565). Topmark, light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Buoy Safe Water
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A safe water buoy is used to indicate that there is navigable water around the mark.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A buoy is a floating object moored to the bottom in a particular place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 565). Topmark, light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Buoy Special Purpose/General
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A special purpose buoy is primarily used to indicate an area or feature, the nature of which is apparent from reference to a chart, Sailing Directions or Notices to Mariners.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A buoy is a floating object moored to the bottom in a particular place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 565). Light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Buoy New Danger Marking
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A new danger marking buoy is a buoy moored on or above a newly identified danger, such as a wreck, designed to provide a prominent (both visual and radio) and easily identifiable temporary (24-72 hours) first response.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Buoy Installation
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An installation buoy is a buoy used for loading tankers with gas or oil.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A buoy is a floating object moored to the bottom in a particular place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 565).

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Beacon Lateral
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A lateral beacon is used to indicate the port or starboard hand side of the route to be followed. They are generally used for well defined channels and are used in conjunction with a conventional direction of buoyage.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A beacon is a prominent specially constructed object forming a conspicuous mark as a fixed aid to navigation or for use in hydrographic survey (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 420). Light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Beacon Cardinal
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A cardinal beacon is used in conjunction with the compass to indicate where the mariner may find the best navigable water. It is placed in one of the four quadrants (North, East, South and West), bounded by inter-cardinal bearings from the point marked.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A beacon is a prominent specially constructed object forming a conspicuous mark as a fixed aid to navigation or for use in hydrographic survey (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 420). Light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Beacon Isolated Danger
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An isolated danger beacon is a beacon erected on an isolated danger of limited extent, which has navigable water all around it.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A beacon is a prominent specially constructed object forming a conspicuous mark as a fixed aid to navigation or for use in hydrographic survey (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 420). Light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Beacon Safe Water
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A safe water beacon is a prominent specially constructed object forming a conspicuous mark as a fixed aid to navigation or for use in hydrographic survey.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A safe water beacon may be used to indicate that there is navigable water around the mark. (UKHO NP 735, 5th Edition). Light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate features.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Beacon Special Purpose/General
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A special purpose beacon is primarily used to indicate an area or feature, the nature of which is apparent from reference to a chart, Sailing Directions or Notices to Mariners.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A beacon is a prominent specially constructed object forming a conspicuous mark as a fixed aid to navigation or for use in hydrographic survey (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 420). Light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate features.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Daymark
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: (1) The identifying characteristics of an aid to navigation which serve to facilitate its recognition against a daylight viewing background. On those structures that do not by themselves present an adequate viewing area to be seen at the required distance, the aid is made more visible by affixing a daymark to the structure. A daymark so affixed has a distinctive colour and shape depending on the purpose of the aid. (2) An unlighted navigational mark.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Light Float
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A boat-like structure used instead of a light buoy in waters where strong streams or currents are experienced, or when a greater elevation than that of a light buoy is necessary.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: The light of a light float is a separate feature, handled as with buoys, beacons, etc.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Light Vessel
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A distinctively marked vessel anchored or moored at a charted point, to serve as an aid to navigation. By night, it displays a characteristic light(s) and is usually equipped with other devices, such as fog signal, submarine sound signal, and radio-beacon, to assist navigation.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: The light(s), fog signal etc. of a light vessel are separate features, handled as with buoys, beacons, etc.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Retroreflector
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A means of distinguishing unlighted marks at night. Retro-reflective material is secured to the mark in a particular pattern to reflect back light.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: The body carrying the retro-reflector is a separate feature.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Radar Reflector
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A device capable of, or intended for, reflecting radar signals.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A radar reflector is usually a tetrahedron or pentagonal corner reflector to facilitate reflection towards the sender (International Maritime Dictionary, 2nd Ed.).

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Fog Signal
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A warning signal transmitted by a vessel, or aid to navigation, during periods of low visibility. Also, the device producing such a signal.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Physical AIS Aid to Navigation
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An Automatic Identification System (AIS) message 21 transmitted from a physical Aid to Navigation, or transmitted from an AIS station for an Aid to Navigation which physically exists.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Virtual AIS Aid to Navigation
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An Automatic Identification System (AIS) message 21 transmitted from an AIS station to simulate on navigation systems an Aid to Navigation which does not physically exist.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Radio Station
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A place equipped to transmit radio waves. Such a station may be either stationary or mobile, and may also be provided with a radio receiver.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: The transmission of a radio station may serve to provide mariners with a line of position (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4). The feature 'radio station' is used to encode the point of transmission of the signal.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Radar Transponder Beacon
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A transponder beacon transmitting a coded signal on radar frequency, permitting an interrogating craft to determine the bearing and range of the transponder.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: The feature 'radar transponder beacon' is only used to encode the technical equipment independent of the structure on which it is located (for example a beacon, light-vessel or tower).

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Pilot Boarding Place
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A location offshore where a pilot may board a vessel in preparation to piloting it through local waters.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Vessel Traffic Service Area
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: The area of any service implemented by a relevant authority primarily designed to improve safety and efficiency of traffic flow and the protection of the environment. It may range from simple information messages, to extensive organisation of the traffic involving national or regional schemes.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Coast Guard Station
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A station at which a visual/radio/radar marine watch is kept either continuously or at certain times only.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: This feature is used to describe the function of the coastguard rather than the building in which the coastguard is sited.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Signal Station Warning
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A warning signal station is a place on shore from which warning signals are made to ships at sea.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Signal Station Traffic
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A traffic signal station is a place on shore from which signals are made to regulate the movement of traffic.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: A signal station is a place on shore from which signals are made to ships at sea (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition).

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Rescue Station
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A place where equipment for saving life at sea is maintained.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: Encodes the service available at this location. The structure housing the service should be encoded separately.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Harbour Facility
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A harbour installation with a service or commercial operation of public interest.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Small Craft Facility
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A place at which a service generally of interest to small craft or pleasure boats is available.
S100_FC_FeatureType.remarks: Encodes the service available at this location. The structure housing the service should be encoded separately.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: Text Placement
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: The Text Placement feature is used in association with the Feature Name attribute or a light description to optimize text positioning in ECDIS.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: BERTHS
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: Place in which a ship is moored at wharf.

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: CANALS
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: An artificial waterway with no flow, or a controlled flow, used for navigation, or for draining or irrigating land (ditch).

S100_FC_FeatureType.name: LIGHTS
S100_FC_FeatureType.definition: A sectored light is a light having one or more sectors, which have different characteristics across, and sometimes within, each sector.
